fields.description: National Geographic photographer David Doubilet explores the glittering world hidden beneath the waves of Papua New Guinea’s Kimbe Bay. After shooting a photo assignment there 17 years ago, he was eager to return.

fields.description: Why do locusts swarm? One scientist thinks he has the answer.
fields.title: Locust Research

fields.description: It's never easy to reintroduce a species, but in Colorado, the lynx is making a comeback.
fields.title: Lynx Reintroduction

fields.description: One of the largest fish in the world, the Mekong giant catfish grows to 10 feet and 650 pounds. Despite its size, it is a gentle giant that survives on a diet of plant matter and algae.
fields.title: Mekong Giant Catfish

fields.description: See the northern leopard frog jump and dive.
fields.title: Northern Leopard Frog

fields.description: Emperor penguin parents overcome starvation, freezing weather, and hungry leopard seals to keep their chicks well fed.
fields.title: Penguin vs. Seal

fields.description: When you're a male gator looking for a mate, you don't need a dance floor to make all the right moves; the warm waters of the Everglades will do just fine.
fields.title: Gator Water Dance

fields.description: This is one confusing animal. Related to the rhinoceros, called a mountain cow, and with a flexible nose like an elephant, Baird's tapirs have to be seen to be believed.
fields.title: Freaks of Nature: A Rhino/Cow/Elephant Cross?

fields.description: A reptile expert tangles with the venomous and infamous Gila monster.
fields.title: Gila Monster

fields.description: Herring have a secret, and funny, way of communicating with each other.
fields.title: Herring Flatulence

fields.description: August 1, 2007—Four rare gorillas were shot in Africa's Virunga park on July 22. Get up close with other Virunga gorillas as rangers patrol the park to prevent another tragedy.
fields.title: Gorillas Executed in Congo Park

fields.description: There is an extraordinary effort to prevent gorilla poaching by making gorillas more valuable alive than dead.
fields.title: Gorilla Tourism

fields.description: The harp seal is found in the North Atlantic and Arctic regions.
fields.title: Harp Seal

fields.description: The great blue heron is ideally adapted for its wetland home.
fields.title: Great Blue Heron

fields.description: A group of tourists lives out a fantasy trip: getting up close and personal with a family of wild gorillas on their own turf.
fields.title: Hanging With Gorillas

fields.description: Where do greyhounds go after their days on the track are over? Long Island Greyhound Transfer (LIGHT) is finding loving homes for these speedy pooches.
fields.title: Greyhound Adoption

fields.description: Watch a grizzly mom teach her cubs the ins and outs of salmon fishing.
fields.title: Grizzly Mom Teaching Cubs

fields.description: Like wolves of the air, Harris's hawks hunt in packs to flush their desperate rabbit prey out in the open, where they're easy pickings.
fields.title: Harris's Hawks

fields.description: No, it's not a new appetizer, nor a new music group. But the hairy sea cucumber does put on a show worth the price of admission!
fields.title: Hairy Sea Cucumber

fields.description: It may be a land crab, but it still has gills and a big thirst for water!
fields.title: Land Crab

fields.description: A hungry jack rabbit is not afraid of cactus needles.
fields.title: Jackrabbit

fields.description: When it comes to hunting prey, spotted hyenas have the formula for success: Divide and conquer!
fields.title: Hyenas

fields.description: You'll only find eyeless shrimp in Madagascar, where their main predators are—what else?—blind cave fish.
fields.title: In the Dark

fields.description: Whale food: these tiny invertebrates play a big role in the ocean's ecosystem.
fields.title: Krill

fields.description: The colorful king vulture reigns over Mayan jungle ruins, where it's well adapted to its scavenger lifestyle.
fields.title: King Vultures

fields.description: Two huge male gorillas square off in the wild in a test of dominance. Which will emerge victorious?
fields.title: Gorilla vs. Gorilla

fields.description: Wild Chronicles dives into a big fish story. While the fish themselves may not be large in size, a herring's importance as a source of food in the ocean is bigger than people know.
fields.title: Herring Hazards

fields.description: A mother gray whale and her calf are on their migration path through Monterey Bay. But first they must get past a pack of killer whales.
fields.title: Gray Whale Migration

fields.description: It doesn't take much to whet a humpback whale's appetite—just a thousand pounds or so a day of fish, krill, plankton, and the like.
fields.title: Humpback Meal

fields.description: Don't tell these howler monkeys to pipe down. They won't unless they are sleeping, which is about 15 hours a day.
fields.title: Howler Monkeys

fields.description: A newly discovered population of orangutans on the island of Kalimantan brings hope for the species' survival.
fields.title: Kalimantan's Orangutans

fields.description: You've got to strike a delicate balance when you're a leopard lugging prey two times your own weight up a tree.
fields.title: Leopard vs. Hyena & Lion

fields.description: Watch this clip of macaws flying in and out of their colony.
fields.title: Macaws

fields.description: Scientists are at work on a new sensor that might help save manatee lives.
fields.title: Manatee Detection

fields.description: The lion's kingdom isn't what it once was. Once upon a time the kingly beast roamed in Europe and America too.
fields.title: Lives of Lions

fields.description: February 20, 2009—Mastiff dogs are becoming increasingly popular in Spain to protect cattle from a growing wolf population.
fields.title: Mastiffs Enlisted to Save Cows

fields.description: The lions' kingdom isn't what it once was.  Once upon a time the king of the beasts roamed in Europe and America, too.
fields.title: Lions Hunting

fields.description: Lions and the Maasai people in Kenya live in tense co-existence.  Innovative programs, such as Lion Guardians and the Predator Compensation Fund, aim to show that the lions are more valuable to the Maasai alive than dead.
fields.title: Lions Imperiled

fields.description: Meerkats take on a dangerous puff adder that encroaches on their territory. Does the mob rule, or does the snake eat tonight?
fields.title: Meerkats vs. Puff Adder

fields.description: The highlands of Papua New Guinea...a place so remote that the people who live here, are among the most isolated. One of the native tribes practices an ageless ritual so secret that it has never before been witnessed by some members of the tribe.
fields.title: Blood Initiation

fields.description: The Galápagos was Darwin's laboratory for the study of the origins of life. See the amazing creatures he studied in 1835—giant tortoises, sea turtles, flightless cormorants, iguanas, and penguins.
fields.title: Galápagos

fields.description: July 22, 2008—Parts of the Northern Hemisphere will soon see a rare total solar eclipse. Find out how it works, where to watch, and more.
fields.title: Solar Eclipse Coming August 1

fields.description: The largest living structure, the Great Barrier Reef spans more than 1,200 miles (2,000 kilometers) of islands and submerged reefs. A plethora of coral thrives here, along with a sweep of parrotfish, surgeonfish, barracuda, and sharks. Narrated by National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Sylvia Earle.
fields.title: Great Barrier Reef

fields.description: August 2, 2010—The Census of Marine Life has released the most comprehensive inventory of ocean life ever created. See some of the deep-sea stars of the "roll call," and find out which regions are the most diverse—and threatened.
fields.title: Record-Breaking Sea-Creature Surveys Released

fields.description: Jan. 15, 2014—Alligators in Florida—fitted with National Geographic Crittercams on their backs—give experts a peak into their daily lives. The video project is the first study to document alligator feeding rates over the course of a day. At one point, an alligator wearing a Crittercam seems to 'pass out,' sinking to the bottom where he remained for more than 90 minutes, only to recover and resurface. One researcher joked he might have been narcoleptic.
fields.title: "Narcoleptic" Alligator & Other Gators "Film" Their Day

fields.description: After traveling 10,000 miles by bus from Washington D.C., National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans landed on Antarctica.
fields.title: Setting Foot on the Seventh Continent

fields.description: In the flooded forests of the Amazon, a development program is sustaining both the environment and the local community.
fields.title: Mamiraua

fields.description: September 26, 2011—A skeleton of a possibly extinct crocodile is among several fossil surprises unearthed  in freshwater caves of the Dominican Republic, paleontologists say.
fields.title: Croc Fossil Found in Cave

fields.description: May 3, 2011—An Australian team, led by National Geographic Society/Waitt Foundation grantee Richard Harris, has made a record-breaking dive in what   may be the world's deepest coldwater cave. But the explorers still   haven't reached the end of this New Zealand cave, thought to lead to the   mysterious source of the Pearse River.
fields.title: Record Cave Dive Leaves Mystery

fields.description: Why did the Maya abandon their magnificent city of Chichen Itza?
fields.title: Maya Pyramids of Chichen Itza

fields.description: A hostile realm battered by titanic winds, Queen Maud Land, Antarctica, is one of the most challenging climbing environments on Earth. Four hard-core climbers describe what it takes to tackle the unexplored peaks at the bottom of the world.
fields.title: Climbing Antarctica's Unexplored Mountains

fields.description: July 31, 2012—NASA has planned one of the most complicated spacecraft landings ever attempted for the Curiosity rover's touchdown on August 6 at about 1:30 am. ET.The complex procedure involves the use of the largest supersonic parachute ever built and a "sky crane" to lower the rover onto the Martian surface. "If any one thing doesn't work just right," says one engineer, "it's game over!"
fields.title: Mars Rover's "Seven Minutes of Terror"

fields.description: Hang out with man's best friend.
fields.title: Dog Investigation

fields.description: Scientists drill in Antarctica to reach a 125,000-year-old lake.
fields.title: Antarctic Dig

fields.description: Prairie dog males fight for mating rights to see who's the top dog.
fields.title: Prairie Dog Romance

fields.description: Having completed more solo trips to the Poles than anyone else on the planet, Børge Ousland is sometimes surprised by who he runs into crossing the vast Arctic tundra.
fields.title: NG Live!: Sheikh of the Arctic

fields.description: November 3, 2008—The Antarctic ozone hole reached its 2008 peak at 10.5 million sq. miles (27.2 million sq. kilometers), short of the 2006 record size of 10.6 million sq. miles (27.5 million sq. kilometers), according to NASA scientists.
fields.title: Ozone Hole Peaks Over Antarctica

fields.description: Unpaved roads can be problematic during Bolivia's rainy season, as National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans found out first hand.
fields.title: The Rainy Season

fields.description: See how artist Fernando Baptista drew the lifelike lioness in our December issue.
fields.title: Artistic Obsession

fields.description: Feb. 5, 2014—In a global collaboration between NASA, ESA, and CSA, a team of more than a thousand scientists and engineers are building the largest telescope ever sent into space—the James Webb Space Telescope. Bigger and more powerful than its famous predecessor, the Hubble Space Telescope, the Webb telescope will be able to observe some of the earliest light that ever existed in the universe and possibly find clues to where we came from.
fields.title: Building the Largest Space Telescope Ever

fields.description: November 26, 2008—Scientists searching the depths of the ocean for undiscovered marine life off the coast of Maine get help from a well-equipped robot.
fields.title: Deep Sea Robo-Help

fields.description: One of the world's most celebrated writers, Isabel Allende, employs her trademark wit and humor to share personal and touching stories of how family, politics, and her Chilean homeland inspire her books.The National Geographic Live! series brings you thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers and performing artists. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: Isabel Allende: A Literary Life

fields.description: March 25, 2008—Pacific leatherback turtles are under serious threat of extinction, as their numbers diminish due to egg poaching and drownings in fishing nets.
fields.title: Saving Leatherback Turtles

fields.description: On March 16, 2011, the MV Oliva, a freighter carrying soybeans from  Brazil to Singapore, ran aground at Nightingale Island in the South  Atlantic Ocean. Fuel from the ship spilled into the water and onto the  shore, and the local population of endangered northern rockhopper  penguins came in contact with the oil. National Geographic Expeditions'  contributor Andrew Evans arrived March 23rd, and filmed what he saw.
fields.title: Endangered Penguins Caught in Oil Spill

fields.description: Sometimes Joel Sartore finds his subject with a little help; in this case it was a perfect moon.
fields.title: Jaguar

fields.description: May 29, 2008—Radiocarbon dating of human remains indicates that the mysterious stone monument was used as a cemetery longer than previously thought.
fields.title: New View on Stonehenge Burials

fields.description: National Geographic photographers describe the moments behind the shots, and editor Annie Griffiths explains the concept behind the new National Geographic book, Simply Beautiful Photographs. This video features stories by David Doubilet, Jodi Cobb, Michael Melford, Sisse Brimberg, and Jim Blair.
fields.title: Making Simply Beautiful Photographs

fields.description: September 17, 2010---Using huge hoses, researchers are vacuuming up marsh bugs along the oiled Gulf coast. By comparing their samples to bugs collected before the spill, teams hope to determine the effects of oil on creatures near the bottom of the food web.
fields.title: Giant Vacuum to Help Bugs in Oiled Marshes?

fields.description: November 2, 2009—Want to meet a Martian or spark lunar conflict? Two former NASA specialists give tips for making the most of Google's 3-D space offerings—and offer hints for finding some little-known gems.
fields.title: Secrets of Google's 3-D Mars, Moon

fields.description: At the Wafer Bay ranger station on Cocos Island, defenders of the park's protected waters fight an uphill battle to safeguard marine life from rampant illegal fishing.
fields.title: Illegal Lines: The Toll on Cocos

fields.description: April 17, 2012—In its final journey to its permanent museum home, NASA's space shuttle Discovery makes a flyover above the U.S. capital. NASA coordinated with the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration to navigate through the restricted air space over Washington, D.C.
fields.title: Shuttle Discovery: Final Flight Over D.C.

fields.description: The team joins a fishing vessel some 25 miles south of Cocos, beyond the no-take zone surrounding the island. Hard work produces scant results in these heavily-fished waters.
fields.title: Four Men, 500 Hooks

fields.description: June 14, 2013—On June 13, aquanaut, oceanographer and marine biologist Sylvia Earle received the Hubbard Medal, the National Geographic Society's highest honor, for distinction in exploration, discovery and research. In light of recent public discussions about women in the sciences, National Geographic asked Sylvia to discuss her experiences as a woman in a field previously considered a man's world.
fields.title: In Her Words: Sylvia Earle on Women in Science

fields.description: June 2, 2010—In behavior never before recorded by scientists, male red-eyed tree frogs are shown shaking their rumps and entire bodies to show dominance. The shaking often precedes wrestling between the two males.
fields.title: Frogs Shake Booties Before Fights

fields.description: August 20--A team of scientists and artists investigates the buildup of marine debris along the Alaskan coast. Their goal: to create art from the trash they find and raise awareness about its impact on oceans and wildlife.
fields.title: Gyre: Creating Art From a Plastic Ocean

fields.description: Jay Dickman describes the power of a frozen moment and how he knows when he has the right shot.
fields.title: Seal Hunt

fields.description: June 18, 2009—In the busy waters off Massachusetts, researchers are hand-tagging humpback whales to learn how to protect the species from potentially lethal collisions with ships.
fields.title: Whales Tagged to Prevent Collisions

fields.description: December 10, 2009—Nearly 500 miles of data-transmitting cable will make Neptune Canada's new Pacific Ocean observatory the largest of its kind. Underwater cameras will also capture seafloor wildlife.
fields.title: Most High-Tech Ocean Observatory Opens

fields.description: Some favorite cityscapes by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Urban Scenery

fields.description: To win choosy females, male bowerbirds swagger, croon, and... decorate.
fields.title: Build It (and they will come)

fields.description: Though it's a landlocked country, Zambia is shaped by water from the Zambezi, Kafue, and Luangwa rivers.
fields.title: Three Rivers

fields.description: National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence  and Filmmaker James Cameron plans to soon dive in a specially designed  submarine to the Mariana Trench in the Pacific Ocean, earth's deepest  point. No human has attempted such a dive since 1960.
fields.title: Cameron Dive First Attempt in Over 50 Years

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner suggests simple things  you can do right now to bring more fulfillment into your life. Today’s  tip: Vacation.
fields.title: Vacation

fields.description: April 18, 2010--The Census of Marine Life's ten-year study has uncovered numerous hard-to-see species unknown to science. For starters, an area the size of a small bathroom revealed 700 species of crustaceans.
fields.title: Tiny New Sea Species Discovered—First Ever Video

fields.description: August 14, 2008—A 10,000-year-old cemetery with hundreds of skeletons is giving unparalleled insight into life in Africa's great desert when it was green and lush.
fields.title: Ancient Sahara Graveyard Found

fields.description: Some favorite landscape photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Sublime Scenery

fields.description: Mark Hanis, the grandson of four Holocaust survivors, says "Never again" to genocide. He formed the Genocide Intervention Network to help save the people of Darfur.
fields.title: Sudan: The Activist

fields.description: Crack the secret code of meerkats.
fields.title: Meerkat Calls

fields.description: December 17, 2009—See the recent "underwater Fourth of July" scientists believe is the deepest volcanic eruption ever seen--with three-foot-wide lava bubbles and flows creeping over the seafloor.
fields.title: Deepest Ocean Eruption Filmed

fields.description: Learn about owls, nocturnal birds of prey.
fields.title: Night Owls

fields.description: March 5, 2008—It is difficult to protect migrating whale sharks once they leave designated no-fishing zones. Scientists and even tourists try to help the threatened species.
fields.title: Largest Sharks Live Dangerously

fields.description: June 30, 2011—NASA's space shuttle has been an icon of the U.S. space  program for the past 30 years. Journey on one of the last shuttle  missions to witness some final "firsts" made aboard this unique  spacecraft.
fields.title: Space Shuttle's Final Days

fields.description: A jawbone discovered in Britain suggests that early modern humans lived in northwest Europe at the same time as the Neanderthal.
fields.title: Human/Neanderthal Co-existence?

fields.description: June 24, 2008—After ten rare mountain gorillas were killed execution-style in a Congo park, Congolese authorities have arrested a senior park official in connection with the slayings.
fields.title: Gorilla Massacre Investigation

fields.description: July 8, 2010—The moon's shadow will envelop Easter Island on July 11 during a total solar eclipse, the first to cross the remote island in about 1,400 years.
fields.title: Solar Eclipse to Darken Easter Island

fields.description: February 20, 2008—Atlantis and its crew safely landed at Kennedy Space Center, after the successful delivery and installation of a new lab for the International Space Station.
fields.title: Shuttle Lands in Florida

fields.description: October 4, 2010—The Census of Marine Life has released its findings of ten years of research and exploration of the world's oceans. The first-ever study of its kind, involving 2,700 scientists from 80 nations, identified more than 6,000 potentially new species. The effort will help researchers observe how marine populations change in response to events such as oil spills and climate change.
fields.title: Biggest Marine Census Complete

fields.description: Underseas specialist Lisa Trotter shows us how diving in Antarctica is not as simple as it may seem.
fields.title: Diving in Antarctica

fields.description: Filmmaker Anna Possberg went to the American Southwest expecting "dead rocks." What she found, and captured in the time-lapse "Petrified Life," was a rugged landscape alive with the shifting of sun and stars.
fields.title: Time-Lapse: Spectacular Landscapes of the Southwest U.S.

fields.description: July 31, 2007—Look in on one of the most dangerous and controversial "catch-and-release" tournaments, as sportsmen and scientists join forces to find and study the ocean's top predators—sharks.
fields.title: Shark Tournament

fields.description: Chris Sharma is one of the world’s strongest climbers. Here he tackles the hardest climb ever achieved—a 200-foot overhanging cave at the top of a mountain in southern California.  He trains for the climb in Spain with his girlfriend, Daila.
fields.title: The Impossible Climb: Chris Sharma

fields.description: Run a gang of rambunctious monkeys out of town.
fields.title: Monkey Trouble

fields.description: Some favorite reptile photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Reptiles

fields.description: Some favorite autumn color photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Fall Foliage

fields.description: For Jodi Cobb, luck plays an important role in taking photographs.
fields.title: Saudi Women

fields.description: Enric and members of the Ocean Now team become stranded on Starbuck Island during an on-shore excursion.
fields.title: Stranded on Starbuck Part 1

fields.description: Jimmy Chin captures people constantly live on the edge.
fields.title: Capturing Yosemite's Superclimbers

fields.description: Catch a crab-snatching octopus red-handed.
fields.title: Octo-Thief

fields.description: A volunteer team of body collectors believe they'll get spiritual merit for carefully handling corpses.
fields.title: Body Collecting

fields.description: March 4, 2008—Two young Asian elephants and a young greater horned rhino were released into the wild in India.
fields.title: Elephants, Rhino Freed in India

fields.description: From deserts to lush tropical forests, one of China's richest treasures is its plant life. Join leading botanist and NG Research & Exploration chairman Peter Raven on a tour of China's regional flora.
fields.title: China's Amazing Flora

fields.description: Get a front-row seat to the show of a lifetime: the creation of life. This close-up view of in vitro fertilization shows egg cells and sperm cells meeting, dividing, and creating a new life.
fields.title: In Vitro Fertilization

fields.description: See what it's like to walk on a glass walkway 4,000 feet (1,220 meters) above the canyon floor in this un-narrated video.
fields.title: Grand Canyon Skywalk

fields.description: August 6, 2012—Early Monday NASA scientists erupted with cheers, tears, and fist pumps at the successful completion of one of the most complicated spacecraft landings ever attempted.After carrying out its "seven minutes of terror" landing sequence with clockwork precision, the Curiosity rover landed wheels-down on the surface of Mars and within minutes sent back pictures of rocky Gale Crater.
fields.title: Mars Curiosity Rover Landing a Success—NASA Jubilant

fields.description: Andrew Evans drives the Great Ocean Road on the southeast coast of Australia.
fields.title: Where's Andrew? The Great Ocean Road

fields.description: January 30, 2007—Join archaeologist Mike Parker Pearson as he takes you through a huge prehistoric settlement that's believed to have housed the builders of Stonehenge.
fields.title: Stonehenge Builders Village

fields.description: Coral reefs are the foundation of many marine ecosystems—and they are in danger.
fields.title: Coral Reefs

fields.description: Mysteries surrounding these ocean giants are finally being solved, thanks to the unique research of 2013 National Geographic Emerging Explorer Andrea Marshall.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: Andrea Marshall: Queen of the Manta Rays

fields.description: The camera trap is one of the many tools photographer Steve Winter uses to catches spectacular images of India's endangered tigers.
fields.title: NG Live!: Trapping Tigers

fields.description: Desert Flower tells the inspiring true story of Waris Dirie, who was catapulted to fame and fortune as a high fashion model after running away from an arranged marriage at age 13. But after years of living a glamorous life, the past comes back to haunt her, and she must face the childhood trauma that forever changed her destiny.
fields.title: Desert Flower

fields.description: Get a closer look at our cuddly cat friends.
fields.title: Cat Spotlight

fields.description: National Geographic Emerging Explorer Ken Banks discusses finding low-tech, low-cost, high-impact solutions to developing world needs at the 2010 Explorers Symposium.
fields.title: Mobile Technology and the Art of the Possible

fields.description: Green turtles gather near Dirty Rock, Roca Sucia, off Cocos Island's north coast.
fields.title: Turtle Dance

fields.description: Is it possible to survive being stuck in quicksand? Jonny Phillips risks life and limb to experience firsthand what it is like to slowly sink into quicksand—just a few feet away from an incoming tide.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Can You Survive Quicksand?

fields.description: The coldest, windiest place on Earth holds 60 percent of the fresh water on the planet. Recent expeditions to the Weddell Sea produced more than 700 new species, including giant carnivorous sponges.
fields.title: Antarctic Ocean

fields.description: Meet a man whose roommates are a pair of river otters.
fields.title: Otter Madness

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler Contributing Editor Andrew Evans gets to sample the many pastries made by Robert and Lorraine McGill, bona fide Falkland sheep farmers and the longtime owners of Carcass Island.
fields.title: Tea Time in the Falklands

fields.description: Chris Johns describes photographing Kalahari lions and how it took him 12 years to capture how majestic they can be.
fields.title: Lions

fields.description: Cinematographer Greg Wilson uses innovative motion picture technology to capture slow-motion images of cheetahs in action, helping us expand our understanding of cheetah biomechanics.
fields.title: NG Live!: Greg Wilson: Cheetahs on the Run

fields.description: Even though Yellowstone borders no ocean, water plays an important role in its life, geography and beauty.
fields.title: Yellowstone's Water "Secrets"

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans is traveling by bus from Washington D.C. to Antarctica, and shot some footage of the last bus he took in North America, traveleing between Colón and Portobelo.
fields.title: Panamanian Party Bus

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans followed his nose to an authentic Argentine pizzeria in Cordoba.
fields.title: Cordoba Pizza

fields.description: Learn the truth behind a mystical creature that lives under the Arctic ice.
fields.title: Narwhal Tooth

fields.description: National Geographic Contributing Editor Andrew Evans found him self surrounded when he arrived in South Georgia. Hundreds of thousands of king penguins swarmed on the beach, and one in particular was quite interested in his boots.
fields.title: Penguin Overload

fields.description: It's Christmas time in Florida, a time when neighbors get together to share some holiday cheer.  But at this Christmas party, some might say they share too much.
fields.title: Nudist Camp

fields.description: A few members of the Ocean Now team spent the afternoon shooting locations on Cocos for a documentary that will be made about the expedition.
fields.title: Slideshow: Island of Waterfalls~Continued

fields.description: March 16, 2010, 2010—National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans recently spotted and filmed an all-black king penguin—a very rare mutant—on the sub-Antarctic island of South Georgia.
fields.title: Mutant All-Black Penguin Found

fields.description: Jan. 17, 2014—A Michigan-based snowmaking company, SMI Snow Makers, is using the latest technology to create snow for the 2014 Winter Olympics in Sochi. Their machines create snow crystals that are like two-week-old snow from Mother Nature. But while Mother Nature takes hours or days to manufacture the crystals, SMI's machines make the snow in 3 to 15 seconds.
fields.title: Making Snow for the Olympics

fields.description: Down a dim corridor...in a tiny, locked room...out of bounds to all but a tormented few, is the cave of spirits...a home for the dead and last hope for the possessed.
fields.title: Cave of Spirits

fields.description: Jan. 31, 2014—Egyptians this month overwhelmingly approved a referendum  on a draft constitution that for the first time included mention of  Nubians. Many Nubians were relocated for construction of the Aswan High  Dam some 50 years ago, and they now hope they can return to their  historic homeland by the Nile.
fields.title: First-Ever Inclusion: Hope for Egypt's Nubians

fields.description: October 28, 2009—NASA this morning launched a prototype of its first new rocket in nearly 30 years. The Ares I-X is a precursor of the rocket that could launch humans back to the moon, and carry the shuttle's replacement spacecraft, Orion.
fields.title: NASA's Ares I-X Rocket Launches

fields.description: On assignment for National Geographic, photographer Jodi Cobb explores a universal question—what is beauty?
fields.title: NG Live!: Jodi Cobb: What Is Beauty?

fields.description: April 23, 2009—An adventure ride down a section of China's Yangtze River could be the last before planned hydroelectric dams flood the rapids and alter the landscape.
fields.title: Final Ride on Wild China River?

fields.description: Join Admiral Richard E. Byrd in 1928 as he leads a team of explorers to the coldest continent on Earth to map the region and claim large tracts of Antarctica for the United States.
fields.title: Byrd Expedition

fields.description: January 4, 2008—After decades of persecution that began under Stalinist rule in the 1930s, Buddhism and monasteries are now on the rebound in Mongolia.
fields.title: Buddhism Rebounds in Mongolia

fields.description: Learn about the art of camouflage among tropical frogs.
fields.title: Tropical Frogs

fields.description: Watch a dung beetle try to make a clean getaway with...dung?
fields.title: Clean Getaway

fields.description: James Cameron's dive to the deepest point of the Marianna Trench joins other exploration 'firsts' in world history.
fields.title: Cameron Dive is an Exploration First

fields.description: An adventurous brother-sister team on a Nat Geo Young Explorers grant kite-ski over 2,000 miles through Canada's Arctic archipelago, fending off polar bears and coping with unfavorable winds and rugged ice along the way.
fields.title: NG Live!: Sarah and Eric McNair-Landry: Kite-Skiing in the Arctic

fields.description: A program in Spain is cleaning up its marine ecosystems by stopping pollutants while they're still on land.
fields.title: Mediterranean Cleanup

fields.description: More favorite humor photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Gag Bag

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans visits the Uyuni Salt Flats in Bolivia.
fields.title: Salt Flats

fields.description: Some favorite travel photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Travel

fields.description: Louis Mazzatenta describes being the first photographer to capture an artifact being unearthed.
fields.title: Terracotta Warriors

fields.description: The Eastern Cape Province of South Africa is home to the Xhosa people, one of the nation's largest tribes. They live in the modern world, but they maintain ancient customs—including one by which boys become men...and starts with pain.
fields.title: Male Circumcision

fields.description: Meet the true Romans of Rome in the neighborhood of Trastevere.
fields.title: Rome's Ancient Neighborhood

fields.description: Some favorite transportation photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: On the Go

fields.description: August 26, 2008—U.S. President George W. Bush has proposed marine national monuments around several U.S.-held islands in the Pacific Ocean. It could become the world's largest protected area.
fields.title: Pristine Islands to Be Protected

fields.description: Egypt's ancient pyramids have left visitors awestruck for thousands of years, and continue to do so today.
fields.title: Destination: Egypt, Pyramids

fields.description: National Geographic's Ocean Now is a project to study the last healthy, undisturbed places in the ocean. Join Dr. Enric Sala and a team of scientists as they spend six weeks exploring the pristine waters of the southern Line Islands in the South Pacific.
fields.title: The Importance of Pristine Coral Reefs

fields.description: April 3, 2009—As tornado season touches down in the U.S., see a high-tech tornado chaser's stunning footage of twisters—and of lightning as you've never seen it, in superslow motion. EDITOR'S NOTE: Tragically, Tim Samaras died in an Oklahoma tornado May 31st, 2013, along with his son Paul, and Carl Young, a frequent partner of Tim's. Read here for more on his death. And click here for a compilation of Tim's videos on National Geographic.
fields.title: Tornadoes, Lightning in Rare Video

fields.description: Seven miles is a long way down... more than a mile deeper than Mt. Everest is up. To reach the deepest part of the Mariana Trench, James Cameron will descend past some pretty amazing milestones. Here's a glimpse.
fields.title: Cameron's Long Way Down: Mariana Trench

fields.description: April 19, 2010—Baby animals, or larvae, virtually unknown to science join algae, burrowers, and bacteria among the hundreds of microbes found by the Census of Marine Life's ten-year study of the sea.
fields.title: Bacteria-size Babies Among Ocean's Smallest Life

fields.description: To many Westerners, Asia has more than its share of suspicious-looking foods. But it's a good bet that there's nothing as popular while at the same time as utterly shocking to outsiders. Could you eat the fetus of a duck...just days from hatching?
fields.title: Duck Fetus Dinner

fields.description: Each year, hundreds of thousands of volunteers gather to clean up coastlines around the world.
fields.title: Coastal Cleanup

fields.description: October 26, 2007—Discovery shuttle astronauts begin the difficult job of attaching an Italian-made module to the International Space Station. The project is expected to take ten days.
fields.title: Shuttle Astronauts Space Walk

fields.description: A reptile expert tangles with the infamous gila monster.
fields.title: Gila Monster

fields.description: USA, 2010, 6 minutesProduced and directed by: Darrell MillerWebsite: www.stormshow.comClassification: Parental Guidance - Coarse LanguageThe Jackson Hole backcountry is the spectacular site for some amazing ski BASE jumps!
fields.title: Radical Reels: Miller’s Thriller: Ski BASE (Custom edit for the Radical Reels Tour)

fields.description: Yosemite's superclimbers hurl above the ground on a rope swing.
fields.title: Swinging From the Alcove

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner introduces the Thrive  Challenge – 8 daily tips about simple things you can do to bring more  fulfillment into your life.
fields.title: Intro

fields.description: September 17, 2007—More than 4,000 artifacts, taken from Machu Picchu in Peru nearly a century ago, will be returned from their displays at Yale University.
fields.title: Yale Returning Peru Artifacts

fields.description: When climbers opt to climb without a rope, they lose the luxury of learning from mistakes. Backyard inventor Matt Maddaloni has engineered a few creative solutions to make the fringe activity of free soloing “safe.” Of course, safe is a relative term.
fields.title: Climbing: Safety Third

fields.description: Some favorite bird photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Birds

fields.description: Some favorite pairs photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: It Takes Two

fields.description: October 31, 2007—The Nature Conservancy has blasted through 1950s-era levees in the Williams River Delta in southern Oregon to save the wetlands and endangered fish species.
fields.title: Explosions May Save Wetlands

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler's contributing editor Andrew Evans is preparing for his next big trip, and so he stopped by the National Geographic Maps division to learn how they create the maps they're famous for.
fields.title: Where's Andrew? Inside the National Geographic Maps Division

fields.description: Moments of song and dance in Sochi show a city gearing up for the  Winter Olympics. Photographer Thomas Dworzak captured these musical  glimpses while on assignment for National Geographic magazine.
fields.title: Musical Moments From Sochi, Russia

fields.description: The on-shore Ocean Now team receives supplies from the ship and will attempt to swim back to the ship in the morning.
fields.title: Stranded on Starbuck Part 2

fields.description: October 15, 2007—Panama's golden frog is a symbol of good luck and prosperity. Now researchers are fighting to save the rare amphibian from a naturally occuring—and deadly—fungus.
fields.title: Panama Golden Frog Threatened

fields.description: July 22, 2010—A sixgill shark—a species often referred to as prehistoric because of its resemblance to sharks living hundreds of millions of years ago—is seen biting on bait at a camera trap deep off Australia. It's part of a project to learn more about deep-sea creatures and possible correlations with human sight and brain development.
fields.title: "Prehistoric" Shark Seen Attacking Deep Bait

fields.description: June 23, 2011—Marine oil spills are usually measured by the amount of oil floating on the surface. But the BP spill in the Gulf of Mexico—from a deep-sea well required a different approach. Find out how one fluid-dynamics expert caused estimates to rise sharply practically overnight.
fields.title: How Gulf Spill Estimates Got It So Wrong

fields.description: June 30, 2010—Diving into natural pools in Belize in the quest for offerings from the ancient Maya, explorers found what's believed to be the country's first recorded fossilized remains. In the course of the expedition, one diver "disappeared" into the pool's floor.
fields.title: Diver "Vanishes" in Portal to Maya Underworld

fields.description: Germany, 2011, 7 minutesProduced and directed by: Danny StrasserWebsite: www.danny-strasser.deClassification: GeneralBobtrack downhill skateboarding is a sport that didn't actually exist- until Danny Strasser began his tour of Europe's tracks.
fields.title: Radical Reels: Concrete Dreams

fields.description: Santeria was brought to the New World by African slaves. They believe their deities are living things, with the same needs as other beings.  But each one has the power to bring good luck...or misfortune.
fields.title: Santeria

fields.description: June 8, 2010--The town of Grand Bayou, Louisiana, has no streets and no cars, just water and boats. And now the Deepwater Horizon oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico threatens the very existence of the Atakapa-Ishak Indians who live there. "We're facing the potential for cultural genocide," says one tribe member.
fields.title: Oil Spill Threatens Native American "Water" Village

fields.description: Discover the secrets of animal-made islands in the rain forest.
fields.title: Jungle Isles

fields.description: September 24, 2009—To help save South Australia's rare black-footed wallaby, researchers are taking joeys from the wild and placing them in surrogate pouches, encouraging wild moms to trigger "backup" pregnancies.
fields.title: Surrogate Moms Boost Wallaby Births

fields.description: Some favorite photos of light by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Light Motif

fields.description: March 23, 2010—In cold Antarctic waters, explorers are finding lush forests of giant, "bad tasting" seaweed and communities of rarely seen sea creatures.
fields.title: Polar Algae Forests Explored

fields.description: Water flows from one sea habitat to another, connecting all the creatures that live within, to one ocean.
fields.title: One Ocean

fields.description: National Geographic Contributing Editor Andrew Evans shoots some scenes from the deck of the National Geographic Explorer as it sails through the Antarctic Peninsula
fields.title: Cruising

fields.description: September 30, 2008— NASA's Phoenix Mars Lander has detected snow falling from Martian clouds, and its soil testing shows further evidence of the planet's watery past, scientists say.
fields.title: Snow Falls on Mars

fields.description: Manila's North Cemetery is the city's largest, with 70 to 80 funerals a day, and more than one million buried here. For most, this would be a chilling place to visit. But to some Filipinos, this sea of tombs and bones is the place they call home.
fields.title: Living in Tombs

fields.description: Some favorite surfing photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Surf's Up

fields.description: August 1, 2013—Though EEG (Electroencephalography) has been around for  decades, now, new technology allows us to detect and measure brain  activity with a lightweight headset and mobile phone. National  Geographic Emerging Explorer and entrepreneur Tan Le demonstrates how  her company's EEG headset and software can be used for a variety of  research purposes.
fields.title: Portable Scanners "Read" Brains on the Go

fields.description: How does a mongoose stand up to a cobra? You might be surprised at the outcome.
fields.title: Cobra vs. Mongoose

fields.description: The inventor of Crittercam tests his camera out on his son.
fields.title: Connorcam

fields.description: May 6, 2010—The mysteries of why and how many animals in the deep sea emit light, known as bioluminescence, continue to puzzle scientists studying the evolution of this natural glow.
fields.title: Why Deep-Sea Creatures Glow

fields.description: January 26, 2012—Researchers have discovered a unique visual attribute that jumping spiders use in attacking and catching prey. The arachnids use what is called image defocus-proven in part by videos that show spiders jumping with deadly accuracy in green light (and fumbling in red).
fields.title: Spiders Jump With Deadly Accuracy in Green Light

fields.description: What's causing killer whales to jump out of the water?
fields.title: Whale of a Leap

fields.description: Some favorite island photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Island Hopping

fields.description: November 8, 2007—Poverty and tradition drive some Haitians to eat cakes of clay, salt, and butter. Nutritionists fight local beliefs about the dish's merits.
fields.title: Clay Eating Discouraged

fields.description: This summer descend into the unknown. Follow Dr. Robert Ballard and his team as they explore the ocean on the E/V Nautilus. Watch live video 24 hours a day on NautilusLive.org.
fields.title: Nautilus Live Summer 2012

fields.description: When James Cameron dives to the lowest point of the Pacific's Mariana Trench, 36,000 feet of water pressure is bearing down on his sub, which feels like 13 cars weighing on each of his shoulders! But he's protected by sitting inside a 2 1/2 inch thick steel ball.
fields.title: Sub Sphere: What Protects Human Deep Divers?

fields.description: March 26, 2012---National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence James Cameron completed a record-breaking dive to the lowest point of the Mariana Trench. See scenes as Cameron's sub, DEEPSEA CHALLENGER, resurfaced, and Cameron emerged from the pilot's capsule around noon, local time (10 p.m. ET March 25th).
fields.title: Cameron Dive Breaks Record

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans is heading out on another epic journey, only we're not exactly sure where he's going. Follow him at his Twitter page www.twitter.com/wheresandrew and check in at Nationalgeographic.com for clues on where he's headed.
fields.title: Where's Andrew? He's On His Way

fields.description: David Doubilet discusses the role of light and the playfulness of sea lions.
fields.title: Sea Lions

fields.description: Canada, 2011, 13 minutesDirected by: Dylan Dunkerton, Kyle Norbraten, Curtis Robinson (The Coastal Crew)Produced by: Ian Dunn, Kyle Norbraten, Darcy WittenburgWebsite: http://www.fromtheinsideout.secondbasefilms.comClassification: General - Coarse Language A partnership between standard setting Anthill Films and the progressive riders of The Coastal Crew, this is a freeride mountain biking film from the athletes themselves.
fields.title: Radical Reels: From the Inside Out (Custom edit for the Radical Reels Tour)

fields.description: September 20, 2007—Yale University has agreed to return thousands of Machu Picchu relics to the government of Peru in what many officials are hailing as a landmark deal.
fields.title: Yale Agrees to Return Machu Picchu Artifacts

fields.description: USA, 2010, 10 minutesDirected by: Don Hampton and Gardy RaymondProduced by: Don HamptonWebsite: www.dh-productions.comClassification: GeneralDH Production's twenty-fifth film adventure showcases their DIY style and blue collar work ethic. No matter where you're at or who you are, it's all about having fun on the bike.
fields.title: Radical Reels: Here We Go Again (Custom edit for the Radical Reels Tour)

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans gives a tour of his cabin on board the MV National Geographic Explorer, which is sailing through Antarctica.
fields.title: On Board the Explorer

fields.description: June 2, 2008—The NASA space shuttle Discovery docked with the International Space Station Monday, bringing a huge new Japanese lab.
fields.title: Shuttle Docks With Station

fields.description: A few members of the Ocean Now team go for a dive at Dirty Rock near Cocos Island.
fields.title: Dive at Dirty Rock

fields.description: December 3, 2010---Cleanup techniques used after the 1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill may have caused more environmental damage than the oil itself.  So different strategies—such as washing sand and returning it to beaches—are helping to clean Gulf of Mexico coasts affected by the oil spill.
fields.title: Exxon Valdez Lessons Applied in Gulf Coast Cleanup

fields.description: Once a year, the Big Apple hosts a unique dinner —the annual gala of the Explorer's Club. The highlight of the evening is the cocktail hour, where the finger food might have legs, a face, or even a tongue.
fields.title: Explorer's Club Dinner

fields.description: After days of lush green banana plantations and tropical lowland jungle, Andrew Evans entered the Sechura Desert–one of the driest places on earth. The vegetation disappeared completely and what started as a bare sandy horizon soon transformed into a flowing wall of dramatic sand dunes on either side. "I felt like I’d been dropped into the world’s biggest sand box and as I watched out the window, the wind blew the sand into new drifts and patterns," he said.
fields.title: Peru With a View

fields.description: Learn about the secret world of fire ants.
fields.title: Fire Ants

fields.description: Andrew Evans spends over 24 hours on his way to his mystery location: Australia!
fields.title: Where's Andrew? A Flight to Oz

fields.description: Digital Nomad Andrew Evans communicates with his followers across the globe in their own language, no matter how exotic.
fields.title: NG Live!: Tweeting in Pitjantjatjara

fields.description: Home to anacondas, the Orinoco river slithers through Venezuela, sustaining an amazing array of creatures, including the world's largest rodent.
fields.title: Orinoco

fields.description: For gorgeous beaches, sangria under the sun, rich cultural history, and a vibrant urban scene, only one choice fits the bill... Spain.
fields.title: Destination: Spain

fields.description: September 27, 2007—NASA's DAWN spacecraft took off from Cape Canaveral, Florida, this morning, kicking off its eight-year mission to study a pair of asteroids beyond Mars.
fields.title: NASA Asteroid Mission Launch

fields.description: February 1, 2008—An 1872 law that allows mining companies to buy land in the U.S. West for about $5 an acre is running smack into 21st-century sensibilities.
fields.title: U.S. Mining Law Contested

fields.description: Celebrated photographer Jodi Cobb looks at the hidden world of modern-day slavery.
fields.title: NG Live!: Jodi Cobb: Human Bondage

fields.description: See what Layla the lioness and her cubs are up to.
fields.title: Lion's Den

fields.description: January 13, 2010—NASA and Florida conservationists joined forces to rescue endangered sea turtles "cold stunned" by record-breaking cold temperatures along the Sunshine State's coast.
fields.title: "Cold Stunned" Turtles Get NASA Rescue

fields.description: May 25, 2011—Quick: In what country is Tungurahua volcano located? See how that and a final question about Mount Everest from host Alex Trebek determined the winner and runner-up for the 2011 National Geographic Bee.
fields.title: 2011 National Geographic Bee's Tense Final Moments

fields.description: July 17, 2008—His eyes covered with metal plates, a thousand-year-old elite mummy has been found surrounded by unfamiliar artifacts—shedding light on a mysterious culture.
fields.title: Unusual Mummy Found in Peru

fields.description: Born and raised in South Africa himself, National Geographic Emerging Explorer Steve Boyes has dedicated his life to restoring and preserving Africa's wilderness areas and the species that call them home.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: Steve Boyes: Reviving the Heart of Wild Africa

fields.description: After witnessing the ritualistic killing of infants and children in his own tribe, 2013 National Geographic Emerging Explorer and humanitarian Lale Labuko co-founded Omo Child to provide safety, care, and education for the children he rescues.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: Lale Labuko: Rescuing Children of the Omo

fields.description: Superman better watch out! Meet Manjit Singh, a world record holder who risks impalement to bend steel using his neck.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Bending Steel With Your Neck

fields.description: August 8, 2008—To get the best look yet at the ice geysers and fissures on Saturn's moon Enceladus, NASA's Cassini spacecraft will fly within 30 miles of the satellite.
fields.title: Saturn Moon Flyby Coming Monday

fields.description: Created by a string of spectacular undersea volcanoes, the islands are surrounded by creatures whose ancestors preceded human beings by millions of years. Narrated by National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Sylvia Earle.
fields.title: Hawai'i

fields.description: Visit the Brain Bank at Harvard, the world's largest brain repository where more than 7,000 human brains are donated, stored, and used for research.
fields.title: Brain Bank

fields.description: October 22, 2007— A Ugandan national park is a sanctuary for some 325 mountain gorillas, about half of the critically endangered species' population.
fields.title: Gorillas Find Refuge in Uganda

fields.description: February 14, 2011—Egyptian officials—who earlier reported that no artifacts were stolen from the Egyptian Museum in Cairo during a looting attempt last month—now say several items are missing from the museum, including some depicting King Tut.
fields.title: Egypt Antiquities Missing

fields.description: Portrait artist Martin Schoeller captures the essence of the individual with a photo essay on how our growing diversity is literally changing the face of America.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: The Power of Photography to Relate

fields.description: September 20, 2006—Journey to Ethiopia's barren great Rift Valley with Anthropologist Zeresenay Alemsegeed, and learn how he discovered "Lucy's Baby," the oldest and most complete human ancestor child ever found.
fields.title: World's Oldest Child

fields.description: January 13, 2012—For the first time, scientists have recorded the defense strategy of the hagfish, which, when attacked, secretes slime from hundreds of pores on its body.
fields.title: Attacking Shark Gagged by Slime

fields.description: November 4, 2009—Part of a growing trend, a Danish family of seven has installed its own wind turbine to produce all the electricity the family needs while reducing its carbon footprint.
fields.title: Family Wind Turbines Gain Momentum

fields.description: Cutting-edge climbers have turned away from Everest and the 8,000-meter trophy peaks in search of virgin terrain. It’s not the height of a peak; it’s the sheer difficulty. Jokingly referred to as “Disaster Style,” the world’s best alpine climbers are figuring out how to do more with less.  A lot less.
fields.title: Mountaineering: Height Doesn't Matter

fields.description: Some favorite photos with a foreground frame by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Frame of Reference

fields.description: Some favorite exploration photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Explorers

fields.description: Go under the cover of darkness to discover the secrets of bats.
fields.title: Hanging Out With Bats

fields.description: Some favorite reader photos of things left behind.
fields.title: What Remains to be Seen

fields.description: September 23, 2010—The BP spill in the Gulf of Mexico sent oil into wetlands frequented by migrating birds. In response, U.S. farmers are flooding fields as far north as Missouri to create alternative, untainted stopovers for birds heading south for the winter.
fields.title: Flooding Farms on Purpose—For the Birds

fields.description: November 28, 2007—South American river dolphins are doing pretty well compared to some river dolphins in Asia. But boat traffic, fishing, and logging are still a threat.
fields.title: Amazon Dolphins

fields.description: One of the strangest ecosystems on Earth lies deep under the ocean.
fields.title: Hydrothermal Vents

fields.description: Chris Johns discusses how aerial shots bring abstraction and pleasant surprises to a photograph.
fields.title: Camels

fields.description: Louis Mazzatenta describes photographing victims of Mount Vesuvius in Herculaneum, Italy.
fields.title: Mount Vesuvius Victims

fields.description: Some favorite dog photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Man's Best Friend

fields.description: Explorer Tim Cope, accompanied by his canine companion, spent more than three years retracing the 6,000-mile route taken by history's greatest conqueror, Genghis Khan, and encountered many curious characters along the way.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: Tim Cope: On the Trail of Genghis Khan

fields.description: July 24, 2013—After an anxious wait, the famous corpse flower finally  bloomed at the U.S. Botanic Garden.  While many visitors expected to  smell the flower's powerful scent, a few were a little disappointed.   Learn the science behind the corpse flower's smell.
fields.title: The Corpse Flower: Behind the Stink

fields.description: December 18, 2006—When Sudan's militias began slaughtering young boys, thousands fled for their lives. Now some of these "lost boys," like John Dau, have made it to the U.S. — and a second chance at life.
fields.title: Sudan: The Lost Boy

fields.description: October 5, 2010—A language  previously unknown to linguists, and spoken by about 800 people has been  documented in the mountains of northeast India. Researchers with  National Geographic's Enduring Voices project recorded the Koro language  for the first time.
fields.title: Hidden Language Recorded

fields.description: March 19, 2008—Destruction of Dominican Republic forests could be offset by farmers growing organic cacao used for chocolate.
fields.title: Chocolate to Save Forests?

fields.description: For Michael Nichols, a combination of elements, particularly energy, comes together to create a moment that works.
fields.title: Gabon Waterfall

fields.description: Completing a marathon is a worthy item for the bucket list. Twenty-six miles is a long way to run, but for the growing number of ultra-runners, that’s just a quick, post work jaunt.  They power through exercise-induced hallucinations, organ failure, and some of the most remote wilderness in the Lower 48.
fields.title: Running: Ever Last

fields.description: August 2, 2010—Featured in a new "roll call" of life from 25 key ocean regions, marine oddities oscillate, swim, and skitter to an ocean "chorus." The animals are all on the Census of Marine Life's newly released species inventory of 25 key areas of the world's oceans. Each area averages more than 10,000 known forms of life, including jellyfish, octopus, sharks, and crustaceans.
fields.title: Sea-Creature Discoveries Spawn Music Video

fields.description: Some favorite water photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Water, Water Everywhere

fields.description: Investigate the acrobatic talents of cats.
fields.title: Acrobatic Cats

fields.description: December 24, 2013—A circus troupe of well-trained cats is touring the United States—proof that the famously stubborn domestic house cat can indeed learn new tricks.
fields.title: Can You Really Train Your Cat?

fields.description: December 16, 2009—The hard to reach "plush toys" on Papua New Guinea have been outfitted with "Crittercams" for the first time. The breathtaking treetop footage is already solving tree kangaroo mysteries, researchers say.
fields.title: Elusive Tree Kangaroos Get Cameras

fields.description: July 28, 2011—For the first time, a team of Russian students won the National Geographic World Championship, which is hosted by Jeopardy! host Alex Trebek
fields.title: Russia Wins Geographic World Championship

fields.description: The mix of moonlight, tide, and temperature triggers an extraordinary explosion of life in these waters. When the conditions are just right, divers can witness the reproduction of corals, snappers, yellowhead jawfish, and nurse sharks. Narrated by National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Sylvia Earle.
fields.title: Gulf of Mexico & Caribbean

fields.description: August 9, 2012—New images from the Mars Curiosity rover show a crater looking like the Mojave Desert, according to a NASA scientist. The rover's cameras also reveal indentations on the pebbly surface, likely created by the spacecraft's landing thruster jets.
fields.title: New Rover Pictures Show Mars Crater "Like Mojave Desert"

fields.description: The world's second largest coral reef is under threat, off the coast of Belize.
fields.title: Belize Coral Reef

fields.description: November 24, 2009—On the 150th anniversary of Darwin's On the Origin of Species, get a  Galápagos tortoise's-eye view via a National Geographic  Crittercam—a first.
fields.title: 'Darwin' Tortoises 'Make' Video

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner suggests simple things you can do right now to bring more fulfillment into your life. Today’s tip: Less TV.
fields.title: Less TV

fields.description: April 30, 2013—NASA's Cassini spacecraft captured high-resolution pictures of a large, mysterious hurricane over Saturn's North Pole.  The eye of this huge storm is 1,250 miles across with cloud speeds as fast as 330 miles per hour.
fields.title: Monster Saturn Hurricane Recorded by NASA

fields.description: Some favorite flower photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Flowers

fields.description: Track a group of snow monkeys that moved to the Texas desert.
fields.title: Snow Monkeys

fields.description: Get a front-row seat to a high-risk brain tumor surgery with a twist: the patient must stay awake and alert to guide his doctors through the surgery.
fields.title: Brain Tumor Surgery

fields.description: Enric Sala and his team of scientists survey and document Flint Island's coral reefs, diving up to 50 times a day to get a complete picture of this marine ecosystem.
fields.title: A Survey of Flint Island's Coral Reefs

fields.description: November 24, 2009—See the only known untouched shipwreck from the Klondike Gold Rush—recently discovered in Canada's Yukon Territory and announced today. The steamboat A. J. Goddard sank in 1901, killing three crew members.
fields.title: Rare Gold Rush Shipwreck Found

fields.description: Some favorite frozen photos by National Geographic readers
fields.title: Freeze Frame

fields.description: Go behind-the-scenes with Martin Schoeller as he photographs twins for the cover of our January 2012 issue.
fields.title: The Twins Cover Shot

fields.description: September 5, 2008—A major earthquake this year in China had a lasting impact on the population of giant pandas, killing at least one of the animals—plus five people who had been working to preserve the species.
fields.title: Quake Pandas Hanging On

fields.description: September 21, 2005—For years man-made changes to the landscape of New Orleans have affected how well it could withstand the wrath of a powerful storm.
fields.title: Doomed New Orleans: Hurricane Katrina

fields.description: Investigate an oddly-toed creature called a tapir.
fields.title: Animal Oddity

fields.description: August 23, 2006—Follow a day-by-day account of Hurricane Katrina's wrath, from its birth in the Atlantic Ocean to its catastrophic effects: flooded streets, flattened homes, and horrific loss of life.
fields.title: Hurricane Katrina Day by Day

fields.description: Take a glimpse inside the unparalleled treasury of iconic images and groundbreaking photography that make up the National Geographic Image Collection.
fields.title: National Geographic Image Collection

fields.description: Uncover the truth behind a missing plague of locusts.
fields.title: Lots of Locusts

fields.description: Join the Gyre Expedition for a close-up look at how garbage impacts our planet. This team of scientists, artists, and educators journeyed into the Alaskan wild this summer to study and gather marine debris. What they collected will become part of a 2014 traveling exhibit that seeks to bring the environmental harm of trash into perspective.
fields.title: Official Trailer - Gyre: Creating Art From a Plastic Ocean

fields.description: March 2, 2011---Deep in Indonesia, motion-activated cameras have recorded two  critically endangered Javan rhinoceroses with their calves. Though the  footage is "great news," only 40 individuals remain—with none in  captivity, conservationists say.
fields.title: Rarest Rhino Filmed

fields.description: More favorite bird photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Birds of a Feather

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner suggests simple things you can do right now to bring more fulfillment into your life. Today’s tip: Exercise.
fields.title: Exercise

fields.description: Adventure athlete Dean Potter walks above Yosemite Falls.
fields.title: Highlining Yosemite Falls

fields.description: March 12, 2010—An extended family was saved from the devastating Chile earthquake of February 27 because they were outside celebrating a child's baptism. An uncle next door, though, did not survive.
fields.title: Earthquake Baptism Saves Chile Family

fields.description: After passing through four countries in one day, National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans had to ditch the buses and hitchhike in order to catch his boat to Costa Rica. The truck driver who picked him up would sing to stay awake.
fields.title: The Singing Truck Driver

fields.description: For underwater photographer David Doubilet, the hardest thing to photograph is the feeling of water.
fields.title: Sting Rays

fields.description: May 24, 2012—Quick: What Bavarian city on the Danube River was the legislative seat of the Holy Roman Empire from 1663 to 1806? Get the answer and see the climax of the 2012 National Geographic Bee, won this year by Rahul Nagvekar of Texas and hosted by Jeopardy's Alex Trebek.On TV: Tune in to the 2012 National Geographic Bee, hosted by Alex Trebek, on PBS. Check local listings.
fields.title: Video: National Geographic Bee's Tense Final Moments

fields.description: London's Thames River is one of the world's most famous urban rivers.
fields.title: Thames River

fields.description: In 1860, missionaries came across ruins in the Cambodian jungle—and discovered a lost city twice as large as Manhattan.
fields.title: Lost City of Angkor Wat

fields.description: August 25, 2008—National Geographic explorers take a three-month adventure through ice and Arctic waters to reach the islands of Franz Josef Land north of Russia.
fields.title: Ice Trek Meets Polar Bears, More

fields.description: March 10, 2010—Confiscated by U.S. Customs agents in Miami, a brightly painted, 3,000-year-old sarcophagus was handed over to Egypt's antiquities chief, Zahi Hawass, on Wednesday.
fields.title: Stolen Sarcophagus Handed Over to Egypt

fields.description: Meet a detective who searches for snakes with his bare feet.
fields.title: Snake Charmer

fields.description: Adventurer Dean Potter takes a walk on a highline over Yosemite Falls.
fields.title: Walking Across Yosemite Falls

fields.description: June 27, 2007—Watch as archaeologists reveal how they identified the long-lost mummy of Hatshepsut, an Egyptian ruler famous for donning the male garb of a pharaoh.
fields.title: Hatshepsut

fields.description: Enric Sala dives with white tip sharks in the Cocos Island Marine Conservation Area.
fields.title: Night Dive With White Tip Sharks

fields.description: Award-winning wildlife photographer Steve Winter and big cat advocate Alan Rabinowitz share inspiring stories of committed people on the front lines of tiger conservation and surprisingly intimate photos of these majestic creatures.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: Steve Winter & Alan Rabinowitz: Tigers Forever

fields.description: National Geographic magazine continues a yearlong series examining the specific challenges and solutions we face as the worldwide population reaches 7 billion people in 2011 with a March story looking at humans' massive impact on the planet. Other stories will follow throughout 2011.
fields.title: Seven Billion: Are You Typical?

fields.description: Is it outer space or underwater? Under the Arctic ice is a cosmos of spectacular and rarely seen bioluminescent creatures with an otherworldly quality.
fields.title: Arctic Abyss: Under the Ice

fields.description: Two of the world's swiftest currents connect off the east coast of Africa, creating some of the richest biological areas of the sea. This ocean is home to the legendary coelacanth fish. Narrated by National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Sylvia Earle.
fields.title: West Indian Ocean

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans stopped on Elephant Island while traveling through Antarctica and got to get a close look at some macaroni and chinstrap penguins.
fields.title: Elephant Island

fields.description: In the town of Lopburi, Thailand, the native primates get special treatment year–round, but especially during the annual Lopburi Monkey Festival
fields.title: Monkey Festival

fields.description: In the far reaches of Papua New Guinea, the Karan tribesmen hunt a delectable dish. It has fur, fangs and claws. And it's not something most Westerners would dare to taste. It's a bat—the flying fox bat, to be precise.
fields.title: Eating Bats

fields.description: December 15, 2006—Most people have heard about the tragedy in Darfur, but what is really happening there?
fields.title: Sudan: Country in Crisis

fields.description: Scientists decode the life-giving riddle of Bolivia's great Akapana pyramid.
fields.title: Mystery of the Akapana Pyramid

fields.description: A firewalking festival called the Anastenaria, revolves around a set of ancient icons that worshippers believe have special powers—to purify, heal and protect. But others view the ritual as sacrilege.
fields.title: Firewalking

fields.description: Some favorite photos of signs by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Everywhere a Sign

fields.description: Killer whales attack and eventually devour a minke whale near the Svalbard archipelago in the Arctic. The hour-long attack was witnessed by naturalists and guests on a National Geographic Expeditions cruise.
fields.title: Killer Whales vs. Minke Whale

fields.description: February 9, 2011—Restoration work is under way  for antiquities damaged during a looting attempt at Cairo's Egyptian  Museum in late January. Museum officials say very little was damaged and  that nothing was destroyed or stolen from the museum.
fields.title: Egypt Antiquities Restoration Under Way

fields.description: National Geographic photographer Brian Skerry describes a magical but  risky experience photographing an enormous right whale. With his new book, Ocean Soul,  Brian showcases his stunning photography and describes his adventurous  life in a gripping portrait of the ocean as a place of beauty and  mystery, a place in trouble, and a place of hope.
fields.title: Ocean Soul: A Magical Day with a Right Whale

fields.description: Jan. 8, 2014—Researchers studying biofluorescent coral also discovered a shark that reflects certain light, along with a stingray, eel, and other fish. The study, published January 8, used special lighting and camera filters to identify more than 180 species of marine fishes that exhibit biofluorescence.
fields.title: Sharks Light Up in Neon Colors

fields.description: In war-torn Sarajevo, Reza finds a girl selling her Christmas presents in order to provide food for her family.
fields.title: Sarajevo

fields.description: In this video Leandro Blanco and Manu San Félix present a revealing look at the amazing sea life at Cocos Island, including an appearance by the extraordinary frogfish.
fields.title: Cocos Revealed

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner suggests simple things you can do right now to bring more fulfillment into your life. Today’s tip: Socialize.
fields.title: Socialize

fields.description: A gunshot wound to the head—was it suicide or homicide? Foray into a real-world forensics case as detectives scramble to solve the mystery.
fields.title: The Real CSI: Crime Autopsy

fields.description: It was the drink that set 19th century Paris reeling.  Banned for almost a century, absinthe is back. And already a new generation is developing a craving for its unique punch—a wallop some compare to marijuana, speed and even LSD.
fields.title: Drinking Absinthe

fields.description: Investigate the relatives of killer whales.
fields.title: It's All Relative

fields.description: Catch a glimpse of the people and wildlife that call this southwestern African country their home.
fields.title: Wild Namibia

fields.description: Some favorite shadow and silhouette photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Shadowcasting

fields.description: March 31, 2011—Scientists are perfecting a naturally based substance that will act like a laundry detergent in oil spills to prevent the oil from sticking to bird feathers. The substance is currently in the testing phase, which is funded by the National Science Foundation.
fields.title: Substance to Stop Oil From Sticking to Birds?

fields.description: Sylvia Earle describes a turtle the team encountered on one of her dives near Cocos Island.
fields.title: We Met Your Turtle

fields.description: Some favorite confrontational photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Fight! Fight!

fields.description: January 6, 2011—Hundreds of life-size human sculptures were recently installed as part of a new underwater sculpture garden off Cancún, Mexico.
fields.title: "Bodies" Make Up Fake Coral Reef

fields.description: August 10, 2010—Up to a billion migrating birds stop over in the Gulf of Mexico region on their annual treks southward. Despite BP's capping of the Deepwater Horizon leak, scientists say the birds may face ill effects from the Gulf oil spill for years to come.
fields.title: Gulf Spill Still Threatens Millions of Migrating Birds

fields.description: Some favorite volcano photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Volcanic Activity

fields.description: Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans explored the Colombian capital of Bogotá and documented the street life in La Plaza de Bolívar.
fields.title: Bogotá Street Life

fields.description: July 30, 2013—The National Aquarium in Baltimore, Maryland, has opened the "Blacktip Reef" exhibit that recreates in great detail the ecosystem of an Indo-Pacific reef.  A few of its new residents will include 20 blacktip reef sharks and a three-flippered green sea turtle named Calypso.
fields.title: A New Home for Blacktip Sharks and a Sea Turtle

fields.description: A crew of eco-minded, risk-loving snowboarders is putting the sweat, toil, and raw adventure back into their sport by foregoing helicopter assistance and accepting the risks and hard work to find the ultimate reward.
fields.title: Snowboarding: Giving the Bird the Bird

fields.description: After a decade-long drought, Aboriginal elders travel the length of Australia's Murray-Darling Basin performing the Ringbalin—a pilgrimage designed to 'dance' the spirit back into the land and heal the rivers. And it appears to work.
fields.title: Dancing the Spirit Back Into Parched Rivers

fields.description: March 27, 2008—Completing the 22nd night landing in shuttle history, NASA's Endeavour landed successfully last night at Kennedy Space Center.
fields.title: Shuttle Lands at Night

fields.description: Dec. 27, 2013—In the exquisite Peacock Room at the Smithsonian's Freer Gallery of Art, one of the oldest Bibles in existence recently went on display. This priceless artifact from the personal collection of Charles Freer contains a  passage not seen in any other biblical manuscript, in which Jesus proclaims the end of Satan's reign on Earth.
fields.title: Mysterious, Ancient Bible on Display

fields.description: July 23, 2010—In an unprecedented effort, scientists and volunteers are moving up to 700 sea turtle nests from the oil-threatened Gulf to Florida's Atlantic coast, a move that might be the only way to save the baby turtles.
fields.title: Gulf Turtle Eggs Relocated

fields.description: November 6, 2009—Along the coast of Abu Dhabi, development is spilling into the sea, smothering the sea grass beds that nourish rare marine mammals called dugongs.
fields.title: Arabian "Sea Cows" Going Hungry?

fields.description: February 15, 2013—Astrobiologist and National Geographic Emerging Explorer Kevin Hand explains how Asteroid DA-14 could be only the beginning of what we can expect from space. With more than a million such objects out there, what can be done to prevent a meteor strike like the one that crashed into Russia this morning?
fields.title: Predicting Meteorite Impacts

fields.description: Watch as a female Australian sea lion finds, captures, and devours a large octopus. The video was recorded with a National Geographic Crittercam deployed on the sea lion as part of research to preserve the species.
fields.title: Sea Lion Attacks Octopus (Non-Narrated)

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans withstood the terrible weather in South Georgia, Antarctica to make this video. "The light, friendly storybook snowflakes quickly turned into pellets of ice that flew at me sideways," he says, "stinging my face like a bunch of angry, icy bees."
fields.title: South Georgia Splendor

fields.description: The Arctic has long been a mysterious, icy wonderland known only to intrepid explorers and the strong indigenous people who call it home.
fields.title: North Pole

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans hiked the last portion of Shackleton's trek from Fortuna Bay in South Georgia, and visited the intrepid explorer's grave to pay his respects.
fields.title: In Shackleton's Footsteps
