fields.description: Take a wild ride with Venom 1, the country's only SWAT team for snakebites, as they handle emergencies from coast to coast. Learn more about the powerful poisons—and how to protect yourself.
fields.title: Venom 911

fields.description: Some favorite weather photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Weather

fields.description: Statues placed under water act as an ecologically beneficial reef.
fields.title: Statue Reef

fields.description: National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence  and Filmmaker James Cameron has announced he will soon operate a  one-man submarine 7 miles deep to the Pacific's Mariana Trench, the  deepest point on earth. Cameron plans to spend as much as 6 hours on the  ocean floor and will film and take specimens for scientific study.
fields.title: James Cameron to Dive to Ocean's Deepest Point

fields.description: May 20, 2008—Seen in cell-phone camera footage, handlers at the Wolong National Nature Reserve in China evacuated more than a dozen panda cubs just after the massive May 12 earthquake.
fields.title: Panda Cubs Rescued After Quake

fields.description: See Nick Nichols's unique aerial contraption in action.
fields.title: Flying Camera

fields.description: October 29, 2012---The U.S. Department of Energy's Oak Ridge National Laboratory has the world's fastest computer. Named Titan, the supercomputer can process 20 petaflops, putting it neck-and-neck with the previous top supercomputer. Oak Ridge's Director of Science, Jack Wells, describes some of Titan's features, as well as some of the lab's supercomputer users, which include one of the world's leading makers of diapers and potato chips. Read full story here. UPDATE: On Nov. 12, 2012, the Top500 list, a ranking of computing systems around the world, named Titan the fastest in the world.
fields.title: Supercomputer Is World's Fastest

fields.description: April 2, 2008—Scotland plans to award 10 million pounds (about 20 million U.S. dollars) for the first viable technology to harness the sea's energy for electricity.
fields.title: $20-Million Contest Announced

fields.description: December 5, 2006—Before he became Mel Gibson's lead consultant on the movie Apocalypto, Maya expert Richard Hansen spent decades exploring their ancient civilization. Watch as he excavates a tomb in the lost city of El Mirador.
fields.title: 'Apocalypto' Consultant Excavates Maya Temple

fields.description: Climbing without a rope represents the ultimate extreme in rock-climbing.
fields.title: Free Soloing Yosemite

fields.description: July 12, 2010—Between Mars and Jupiter, the European Space Agency's Rosetta spacecraft captured the first close-up images of asteroid 21 Lutetia Saturday, with scientists comparing the pictures to "the discovery of a new world."
fields.title: "New World" Asteroid Photographed Up Close

fields.description: In Zimbabwe people have access to modern medicine. Yet many of the people still have powerful ties to the world of the spirits. And when modern remedies fail, many turn to traditional healers.
fields.title: Spirit Healers

fields.description: June 14, 2010—Japan's Hayabusa, the first spacecraft to land on an asteroid and return to Earth, made a fiery reentry over southern Australia Sunday night. Scientists hope the craft's capsule contains samples from the asteroid Itokowa.
fields.title: Hayabusa Spacecraft's Fiery Return From Asteroid

fields.description: Find out why black bears are being accused of stealing human food.
fields.title: Bear Bandits

fields.description: February 17, 2010—A new laser system can kill mosquitoes without harming other insects, as shown in slow–motion video. It's all part of the effort to combat malaria.
fields.title: New Laser Zaps Mosquitoes in Slow-Motion Video

fields.description: Jan. 16, 2014—Researchers have discovered skulls and other human remains in a submerged cenote considered taboo by locals near the ancient city of Mayapán in Mexico's Yucatán peninsula. The cenote is considered sacred and local residents both respect and fear it.
fields.title: Skulls Found in "Evil" Maya Sinkhole

fields.description: The ocean produces 70 percent of the Earth's oxygen and drives our weather and the chemistry of the planet. Most of the creatures on Earth live in the sea. But our knowledge of the ocean is far outstripped by our impact on it. Narrated by National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Sylvia Earle.
fields.title: Oceans Overview

fields.description: Click off the crime show and foray into the real world of forensics. At the unique open-air crime lab known as the Body Farm, decomposing corpses help detectives solve murders.
fields.title: Body Farm

fields.description: USA, 2011, 8 minutesProduced and directed by: Curtis MorganWebsite: http://artofflightmovie.com/Classification: GeneralFeaturing Travis Rice and a cast of riders, this excerpt from one of the year's hottest snowboarding films is chock-full of action and mind-blowing stunts captured in stunning high-definition.
fields.title: Radical Reels: The Art of Flight (Special Edit)

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner suggests simple  things you can do right now to bring more fulfillment into your life.  Today’s tip: Finances.
fields.title: Finances

fields.description: September 19, 2005—See cameraman Mike Theiss' amazing images of hurricane Katrina's landfall at Gulfport, Mississippi.
fields.title: Katrina Extreme: Mississippi Destruction

fields.description: It has a big, bulbous head...beady black eyes...and eight squirming tentacles. It's the octopus. Many would call it ugly and disgusting. The one thing they wouldn't call it is dinner.
fields.title: Eating Live Octopus

fields.description: In celebration of the 50th anniversary of the first Americans to reach the summit of Mount Everest, climbers Conrad Anker and Emily Harrington, writer Mark Jenkins, and naturalist Alton Byers discuss the history and future of the world's highest peak.
fields.title: NG Live!: The Call of Everest

fields.description: Endangered sea turtles are making a comeback thanks to the T.E.D.—the Turtle Excluder Device.
fields.title: Turtle Excluder

fields.description: December 31, 2009—A new program in Japan is helping giant salamanders get past dams built to control flooding so the rare amphibians can lay their eggs upstream.
fields.title: Giant Salamanders Helped to Spawn

fields.description: Jan. 22, 2014—In Crystal Rivers, Florida, residents depend on a healthy manatee population for the local economy. But with the largest number of manatee deaths in recorded history, 2013 was a dire year, with more than 800 deaths for these friendly giants.
fields.title: Manatee Death Toll Highest Ever Recorded

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans wanders the lonely, windy city of Rio Gallegos in Argentina while waiting for his departure to Ushuaia.
fields.title: The Winds of Rio Gallegos

fields.description: National Geographic Emerging Explorer and roboticist Chad Jenkins explores how to get robots out of the lab and into the real world performing useful and important work—whether that be in the home, outer space, or war-torn battlefields.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: Chad Jenkins: Robots Among Us

fields.description: May 22, 2013—Quick: Because Earth bulges at the Equator, the point that is farthest from Earth's center is the summit of a peak in Ecuador. Name this peak. Get the answer and see the climax of the 2013 National Geographic Bee, hosted by Jeopardy's Alex Trebek. This Bee marks Trebek's final time as host after 25 years.
fields.title: 2013 National Geographic Bee's Final Moments

fields.description: Mysterious and spectacular ancient monuments confound scientists and dazzle travelers to this Andean nation.
fields.title: Destination: Peru

fields.description: A large field in Arkansas contains fossilized tracks belonging to a predator closely related to the T-Rex.
fields.title: Arkansas Dinosaurs?

fields.description: Herpetologist Jesus Rivas gets bitten by a stubborn anaconda. How does he escape from the snake's powerful bite?
fields.title: Anaconda Bite

fields.description: Catch dumpster-diving polar bears in the act.
fields.title: Dumpster Divers

fields.description: Spy on clever dolphins.
fields.title: Dolphin Antics

fields.description: Jan. 30, 2014---Long  gone are the days when young athletes suffering from concussion symptoms were told to "shake it off."  As more professional athletes acknowledge health problems from concussions,  researchers are studying how the same kinds of injuries affect  children.
fields.title: Cracking Down on Concussions

fields.description: Brazil boasts fabulous beaches, vast, unspoiled swaths of Amazon rainforest, Pantanal wetlands, and, of course, Rio de Janeiro's Carnival.
fields.title: Destination: Brazil

fields.description: Richard Ambrose and Jonny Phillips use an infrared camera to show a microwave oven in action.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Microwave Ovens

fields.description: USA, 2011, 4 minutesDirected and produced by: Bill DonavanWebsite: www.dangerouscircus.comClassification: GeneralLook at me- and my headcam!
fields.title: Radical Reels: Narsicame

fields.description: On an ancient island, a modern lagoon provides beauty and an enormous hot tub for locals and tourists alike.
fields.title: Blue Lagoon

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner suggests simple  things you can do right now to bring more fulfillment into your life.  Today’s tip: Take pride.
fields.title: Pride

fields.description: Monterey Bay boasts an undersea canyon that is deeper than the Grand Canyon. This rich environment is home to krill, Humboldt squid, mola mola, and a plethora of tiny animals that thrive in giant kelp forests. Narrated by National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Sylvia Earle.
fields.title: Monterey Bay

fields.description: Wild Detectives uses special cameras to see how owls see in the dark.
fields.title: Night Vision

fields.description: Challenger Deep in the Mariana Trench near Guam is the deepest spot on Earth. How do we know? We didn’t look for it. We listened.
fields.title: Sounding the Deepest Spot on Earth

fields.description: After ten weeks on the road, taking buses from Washington D.C. to Antarctica, National Geographic contributing editor Andrew Evans returns to where he started his trip, National Geographic Headquarters, and thanks everyone for following him on his journey.
fields.title: Andrew Returns

fields.description: Brian Skerry braves the waters of the Antarctic for a very up-close view of the right whale.
fields.title: NG Live!: Diving With Whales

fields.description: Using the ground beneath his feet as a canvas, camera obscura photographer Abelardo Morell inspires fresh appreciation for America's national parks.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: The Power of Photography to Celebrate

fields.description: Some cultures invoke the spirits in ways outsiders might find strange or even shocking—allowing their bodies to be pierced with skewers and hooks. But each year, more than a million Malaysian Hindus take part in this ceremony called, Thaipusam.
fields.title: Thaipusam

fields.description: Some favorite angular and perspective photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Odd Angles

fields.description: Keith Bellows, editor in Chief of National Geographic Traveler, launches our new series, "Where's Andrew?"
fields.title: Where's Andrew?

fields.description: Find out how giant sea turtles cleverly avoid becoming shark bait.
fields.title: Turtle Races

fields.description: Typically, sea kayakers dream of calm waters and soft tail winds. It’s preferable to navigate around waves and whirlpools. A team of young adventure kayakers redraw the sport’s horizon by seeking out the sea’s most turbulent places–tidal races–and diving right in.
fields.title: Sea Kayaking: A Different Kind of Race

fields.description: The team shares photographs from a hike through Cocos Island’s rain forest, from Wafer Bay to Genio Falls, then up and over a ridge to Chatham Bay.
fields.title: Slideshow: Cocos-Forest Primeval

fields.description: Visit a dog with a real nose for detective work.
fields.title: Dog Detective

fields.description: February 21, 2008—Mongolia's harsher, less predictable, and increasingly warmer weather is helping to drive a migration of nomadic herders from the steppe into cities.
fields.title: Climate Drives Nomads to Cities

fields.description: A recent report claims harvesting the sun's energy from space could be a cost-effective way to power the earth.
fields.title: Solar Power from Space?

fields.description: May 26, 2010—Quick: Where do they speak Tswana? Get the answer in the tense final moments of the 2010 National Geographic Bee, hosted by Jeopardy!'s Alex Trebek.
fields.title: 2010 National Geographic Bee Final Moments

fields.description: January 17, 2008—Park rangers in Belize are up against loggers and poachers in this segment from Wild Chronicles' Climate Connections series.
fields.title: Rangers Protect Belize Reserve

fields.description: January 15, 2009—Residents of the Caribbean island of Montserrat call one of their edible frog species mountain chicken, but this edible amphibian is now endangered, conservationists say.
fields.title: "Mountain Chicken" Frog at Risk

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner introduces the Thrive Challenge – 8 daily tips about simple things you can do to bring more fulfillment into your life.
fields.title: Intro

fields.description: February 7, 2008—NASA launched the space shuttle Atlantis Thursday afternoon for a mission to attach the European Space Agency's Columbus laboratory to the International Space Station.
fields.title: Space Shuttle Atlantis Launches

fields.description: Crowning the top of the world, the frozen Arctic Ocean provides an unlikely home for a spectrum of enchanting creatures. Above the ice and below, beluga whales, narwhals, bowhead whales, walruses, and murres prosper. Narrated by National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Sylvia Earle.
fields.title: Arctic Ocean

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner suggests simple things    you can do right now to bring more fulfillment into your life. Today’s    tip: Meditate.
fields.title: Meditate

fields.description: The night belongs to whitetip reef sharks, which sleep by day but patrol the seafloor after dark near Cocos Island.
fields.title: River of Sharks

fields.description: Monitor a gang of mischievous rooks during a campground invasion.
fields.title: Rook Mayhem

fields.description: April 4, 2007—See the freshly uncovered evidence that may prove ancient cities on Egypt and Palestine's coast were devastated by a massive Mediterranean volcanic eruption.
fields.title: Atlantis Volcano Devastated Ancient Egypt?

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner suggests simple things you can do right now to bring more fulfillment into your life. Today’s tip: Sleep.
fields.title: Sleep

fields.description: Jan. 3, 2014—See our ancient ancestors come to life through  paleoartist John Gurche's realistic human likenesses for the  Smithsonian's Hall of Human Origins. "The human story is really nothing  short of the story of a little corner of the universe becoming aware of  itself," says Gurche.
fields.title: Ancient Ancestors Come to Life

fields.description: After traveling for over 45 days through the Americas by bus National Geographic Traveler contributing editor finally reaches his ultimate goal: Setting foot on the seventh continent, Antarctica.
fields.title: Arrival in Antarctica

fields.description: Some favorite reflective photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Reflections

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans is traveling 10,000 miles by bus--from Washington D.C. to Antarctica. In this leg of his journey, he rides along with the locals in Guatemala.
fields.title: Riding Guatemala's Colorful Buses

fields.description: Trek through the swamps of Arkansas to search for a giant anaconda.
fields.title: Arkansas Anaconda

fields.description: February 1, 2013—In Mali and Afghanistan, locals hid priceless historic artifacts from occupying forces. Archaeologist and National Geographic Fellow Fred Hiebert explains why people risk their lives for their cultural heritage.
fields.title: Treasure Hide? History in Peril

fields.description: Some favorite faith and devotion photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Gotta Have Faith

fields.description: National Geographic photographer Brian Skerry describes one of his  scariest adventures -- swimming at night with hundreds of gigantic  Humboldt squid. With his new book from National Geographic, Ocean  Soul, Brian showcases his stunning photography and describes his  adventurous life in a gripping portrait of the ocean.
fields.title: Ocean Soul: Night Swimming with Sea Monsters

fields.description: January 11, 2008—Climbing to the top of the world is an often fatal quest. But for many climbers, reaching the peak is a thrill like no other.
fields.title: Surviving Deadly Everest

fields.description: Enric Sala talks about his amazing dive in Cocos where he saw hammerhead sharks and a "bait ball" with a school of red snappers and other fish.
fields.title: Hammerhead Sky

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans is traveling from Washington D.C. to Antarctica by bus, but he had to hitch a ride with the National Geographic Sea Lion in order to cross the Darién Gap.
fields.title: Onboard the National Geographic Sea Lion

fields.description: Get a glimpse of Sita the tiger with her cubs.
fields.title: Sita the Tiger

fields.description: Award-winning photographer Steve Winter documents the disappearance of Asian Tigers in India, Sumatra, and Thailand.
fields.title: NG Live!: Steve Winter: On the Trail of the Tiger

fields.description: November 22, 2009—Oil-eating tubeworms and 15-tentacled sea cucumbers are among the 5,000 deep-dwelling species identified by the Census of Marine Life, a ten-year effort to chronicle life in the deep ocean.
fields.title: "Dumbo" Other Deep-Sea Oddities Found

fields.description: A Kung Fu Master proves to Richard Ambrose that you really can break two brick blocks with just your hand and without the use of trickery.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Kung Fu Strength

fields.description: Join a team of medical researchers on a journey into the mind as they probe the mysteries of memory. Are incredible memory feats due to DNA or sheer determination?
fields.title: Memory Man

fields.description: May 20, 2009—Watch the tense final moments of the 2009 National Geographic Bee as host Alex Trebek grills the finalists in Washington, D.C.
fields.title: GeoBee 2009: Winning Question

fields.description: July 14, 2010—See the first footage of Kawio Barat, one of the world's largest underwater volcanoes. The roiling, 10,000-foot-tall (3,000-meter-tall) peak is crawling with crustaceans near Indonesia.
fields.title: Giant Undersea Volcano Revealed

fields.description: Some favorite underwater photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Under the Sea

fields.description: March 26, 2012—In a state-of-the-art submersible, National Geographic explorer-in-residence and filmmaker James Cameron reached the deepest point of the Mariana Trench, breaking a world record for the deepest solo dive.
fields.title: James Cameron Breaks Solo Dive Record

fields.description: November 28, 2007—A nearly cloudless satellite image is the most geographically accurate and true-color map of the southern continent—at ten times the resolution of previous NASA views.
fields.title: Antarctica Images Best Yet

fields.description: Conduct surveillance on a town invaded by a huge flock of crows.
fields.title: Crow Invasion

fields.description: They built the pyramids as tombs for their pharaohs, but the ancient Egyptians weren't obsessed with death...they were in love with life.
fields.title: Tombs of Ancient Egypt

fields.description: Covering 72 percent of the Earth and supplying half its oxygen, the ocean is our planet's life support system—and it’s in danger. Watch this video to learn why a healthier ocean means a healthier planet, and find out how you can help.
fields.title: Why the Ocean Matters

fields.description: May 17, 2013—The booming tourism industry aimed at putting people on the peak of Mt. Everest has radically changed the lives of Nepal's Sherpas. National Geographic Young Explorer and photographer Max Lowe recently spent two months in Nepal's Khumbu region, documenting some of those changes.
fields.title: Everest Tourism Changed Sherpa Lives

fields.description: May 21, 2008—Host Alex Trebek asks the last three questions of the final round in the 2008 National Geographic Bee held in Washington, D.C.
fields.title: Winning 2008 GeoBee Questions

fields.description: Go behind the scenes at a factory that makes top-of-the-line artificial legs that contain hydraulics, brakes, microchips, and miniature motors.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Prosthetic Leg

fields.description: June 9, 2011—The  March 11 earthquake and tsunami left more than 28,000 dead  or missing. See incredible footage of the tsunami swamping cities and turning buildings into rubble.
fields.title: Rare Video: Japan Tsunami

fields.description: A company is helping to improve endangered coral reefs, thanks to people who want to "sleep with the fishes."
fields.title: Reef Balls

fields.description: Enric Sala has the best dive of his life at the reefs off Vostok Island. Watch as he describes the massive schools of fish, sharks, and beautiful coral he saw while studying this pristine coral reef.
fields.title: Vostok: 'The Most Amazing Place I've Ever Seen'

fields.description: Radical Reels People's Choice Award - Sponsored by The Banff CentreUSA, 2011, 22 minutesProduced & directed by: Nick Rosen & Peter MortimerWebsite: www.senderfilms.comClassification: Parental Guidance - Coarse LanguageWelcome to the wildest competition known to man - the speed record on the Nose route of El Capitan. For 50 years, the best climbers in the world have been one-upping each other on this massive granite monolith in Yosemite National Park, racing up 3,000 feet of vertical rock in under three hours, and risking life and limb to shave mere seconds off the record time.
fields.title: Radical Reels: Reel Rock: Race for the Nose

fields.description: In the jungles of Central Africa, holy men from a religion called Bwiti believe they have found a way to talk to the dead.  The key is a mind-altering drug that brings on violent, terrifying visions, and occasionally even death.
fields.title: Speaking to the Dead

fields.description: Throughout National Geographic magazine's 2012 photo seminar, we asked  our photographers three questions. Their answers surprised us.
fields.title: Inside the Photo Seminar

fields.description: Your brain waves may change the appearance of art by 2013 National Geographic Emerging Explorer Raghava KK, but at the same time his art may change you through interactivity that shows the many perspectives within every story.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: Raghava KK: Coloring Outside the Lines

fields.description: Andrew Evans woke up bright and early on new year's day and stood outside the bus stop in front of National Geographic headquarters, where he began his 10-week, 10,000 mile journey to Antarctica. At 11:26 a.m., right on schedule, the S2 Metrobus pulled up and he hopped on, the adventure begun.
fields.title: And He's Off!

fields.description: Photographer Steve Winter pays an unnerving visit to Thailand's Tiger Temple.
fields.title: NG Live!: Tiger Temple

fields.description: May 22, 2008—NASA's Phoenix Mars Lander is scheduled to touch down near the planet's north pole Sunday and begin its search for signs of life on Mars.
fields.title: Polar Probe to Land on Mars

fields.description: September 25, 2008—Tests of the pink birds, which live in Kenya's Lake Nakuru, show heavy metals and pesticides—leading experts to suspect growing industry as the cause.
fields.title: Pesticides Killing Flamingos?

fields.description: Some favorite pattern photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Pattern Recognition

fields.description: While traveling through Antarctica, National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans spotted an extremely rare melanistic penguin. This "one in a zillion" bird's all-black coloring is result of a genetic defect, but Evans said, he seemed to get along well with all the other penguins.
fields.title: Black Penguin

fields.description: For those who brave the rapids, the Colorado River offers a glimpse of an untouched world.
fields.title: River Rafting

fields.description: Hear the gripping account of Australian Douglas Mawson's 95-mile trek across Antarctic ice battling hunger, dire circumstances, and deadly crevasses, as told by award-winning writer and adventurer David Roberts.
fields.title: NG Live!: Alone on the Ice: The Best Survival Story You've Never Heard

fields.description: In New Mexico, the Mescalero Apache reservation prepares for a coming-of-age ritual. Over the span of four days, young Apache girls will pass through ancient tests of strength, endurance, and character that will make them women.
fields.title: Apache Girl's Rite of Passage

fields.description: National Geographic's Digital Nomad, Andrew Evans, bids farewell to  Japan after spending a month tweeting and blogging his way across the  country.
fields.title: Sayonara Japan Music Video

fields.description: December 21, 2006—By the age of 13, Emmanual jail was an experienced combat veteran in the Sudanese civil war. Today he is a rapper and a rising star on the world music scene.
fields.title: Sudan: The War Child

fields.description: In Florence, artisans create beautiful craftworks using techniques developed over centuries.
fields.title: Florence Artisans

fields.description: December 6, 2007—Egyptian Maus may descend from the first domesticated cats in the world. One woman is working to help save them.
fields.title: Ancient Cat in Today's Egypt

fields.description: January 26, 2012—A powerful geomagnetic storm sparked extreme auroras in the skies over Abisko National Park in Sweden on January 24. This time-lapse video of the sky show, shot over three hours by Lights Over Lapland photographer Chad Blakley, also shows some of the participants during an aurora borealis photo expedition.
fields.title: Intense Auroras Fueled by Sun Storm (Silent)

fields.description: Calling from a remote Pacific island, Explorer-in-Residence Enric Sala gives an update on the Pitcairn expedition and answers questions from around the world.  Site of the infamous HMS Bounty mutiny, Enric is there on a mission to help save one of the last pristine stretches of water left on Earth.
fields.title: Live interview from Pitcairn with Enric Sala

fields.description: Famed painter Chéri Chérin works at night, when the day's bustle yields to inspiration. His art seeks to preserve an important cultural moment in Kinshasa, a city buoyed by creativity in the face of crime, want, and government dysfunction.
fields.title: By Night, Artist Captures Kinshasa

fields.description: Tweeting across 10,000 miles, Digital Nomad Andrew Evans is joined by thousands of followers who track in real time his epic journey from Washington, D.C., to Antarctica.
fields.title: NG Live!: Andrew Evans: Digital Nomad

fields.description: May 22, 2008—People living permanently on the islands to serve tourists may represent an "invasive species" that could destroy the unique and iconic habitat.
fields.title: Humans Threatening Galápagos

fields.description: Canada, 2011, 8 minutesDirected by: Dave Mossop, Eric CroslandProduced by: Malcolm Sangster, Eric CroslandWebsite: http://sherpascinema.comClassification: General – Coarse LanguageBig mountains and steep lines are the focus in this high energy excerpt from the award-winning feature film ‘All.I.Can.'*This custom edit contains only footage not seen in the Banff Mountain Film Festival World Tour's ‘All.I.Can: The Short Cut.'
fields.title: Radical Reels: All.I.Can: Perseverance (Custom edit for the Radical Reels Tour)

fields.description: National Geographic Fellow Sandra Postel views the world through a water lens, advocating for all to make simple and easy changes to their everyday lives that will help "Change the Course" of the Earth's precious supply of freshwater.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. fields.title: NG Live!: Sandra Postel: Troubled Waters

fields.description: January 30, 2009—Each winter, hordes of manatees congregate in the warm waters of the Florida Everglades. And a National Geographic researcher is working to see if the species is recovering.
fields.title: Manatees Head South

fields.description: Photojournalist David Guttenfelder offers a glimpse inside North Korea's tightly controlled society, where the truth is rarely simple.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. fields.title: NG Live!: The Power of Photography to Reveal

fields.description: A modern marvel of engineering, the invention of the space shuttle changed America's space program forever. Take a journey through the incredible science of aerospace engineering and the shuttle's history.
fields.title: Space Shuttle History

fields.description: December 19, 2006—Remote, complicated, and dangerous, the conflict in Darfur is extremely difficult for journalists to cover. But when National Geographic's Paul Salopek was taken prisoner, the stakes were life and death.
fields.title: Sudan: The Reporter

fields.description: With the DeepSee submersible, Enric Sala, Sylvia Earle, Jorge Cortés, and other expedition scientists probe depths beyond the reach of scuba divers at Cocos Island and Las Gemelas seamounts.
fields.title: Into the Abyss

fields.description: Some favorite butterfly photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Butterfly Effects

fields.description: Polar explorers Børge Ousland and Mike Horn battle pitch-darkness, subzero gales, and polar bears to become the first to reach the North Pole in the winter.
fields.title: NG Live!: To the North Pole in Darkness

fields.description: September 1, 2010---As Atlantic hurricane season heats up, storms could send toxic hydrocarbons lingering from the Gulf of Mexico oil spill surging inland, scientists say.
fields.title: Hurricanes Could Carry Gulf "Oil" Inland

fields.description: April 21, 2011—Scientists  use cameras and sonar near the U.S. Virgin Islands to 'see' the sea floor and find out how fish and  other sea life use the underwater habitats,  which include coral reefs and sea grasses.
fields.title: Scientists "See" Ocean Floor via Sonar

fields.description: National Geographic Young Explorer Emily Ainsworth is a fearless anthropologist/photographer who joins a Mexican circus and gains privileged insight into the brighter and darker sides of a world of magic, masquerade, and skill.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. fields.title: NG Live!: Emily Ainsworth: Inside a Mexican Circus

fields.description: A unique black penguin pops up during Digital Nomad Andrew Evans's trip to Antarctica.
fields.title: NG Live!: "Discovering" the Black Penguin

fields.description: What happens when you send a request out to the world to chronicle, via video, a single day on Earth? You get 80,000 submissions and 4,500 hours of footage from 192 countries, all shot on the same day. Producer Ridley Scott and Oscar-winning director Kevin Macdonald took this raw material and created Life in a Day, a groundbreaking, feature-length documentary that portrays this kaleidoscope of images we call life. Prepare to be amazed.
fields.title: Life in a Day

fields.description: July 16, 2009—See NASA's newly restored video of the first ever moonwalks in 1969—and find out what it took to capture it.
fields.title: "New" Moon Landing Video

fields.description: To save the waters of the Conasauga, one farmer is giving his land back to the river.
fields.title: Conasauga River

fields.description: February 27, 2009—Microchip-implanted penguins in Argentina are helping scientists by just doing what comes naturally on the birds' favorite "highway" to the sea.
fields.title: Penguins (Cutely) Count Selves

fields.description: Accomplished climber Mike Libecki and photographer Cory Richards battle extreme cold and furious katabatic winds in an epic, ten-day climb to the summit of the untouched Bertha's Tower at the bottom of the world.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: Mike Libecki & Cory Richards: Antarctic Mountain Climbing

fields.description: The Mediterranean sea bed holds treasures from thousands of years of trade across its waters. Among the scattered shipwrecks, divers can also find rich coral reefs full of natural wonders, as well as the racing bluefin tuna. Narrated by National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Sylvia Earle.
fields.title: Mediterranean Sea

fields.description: When they hit a dead end in their research, scientists unraveling the mysteries of memory turned to an unexpected source for help. Do taxi drivers grow bigger brains by remembering routes?
fields.title: London Taxi Drivers' Brains

fields.description: Frontier (Custom edit for the Radical Reels Tour)USA, 2010, 20 minutesProduced & directed by: Rush SturgesWebsite: www.river-roots.comClassification: GeneralFrom Mexico to Iceland, Frontier features huge waterfalls, remote areas, breathtaking scenery, and some of the most challenging whitewater ever paddled.
fields.title: Radical Reels: Frontier (Custom edit for the Radical Reels Tour)

fields.description: National Geographic contributing editor Andrew Evans learns about (and cuddles with) endangered Tasmanian Devils while traveling through Australia. To read more from Andrew's journey, visit www.nationalgeographic.com/wheresandrew.
fields.title: Where's Andrew? Tasmanian Devils

fields.description: More than 40 years after setting foot on the moon during the historic Apollo 11 mission, American astronaut Buzz Aldrin makes a passionate, thoughtful case for sending humans to the red planet by 2035.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.

fields.description: Hear how a camera protected photographer Mattias Klum during a king cobra attack.
fields.title: King Cobra

fields.description: At the Peninsula Valdez, a pod of orcas undertakes a daring dining ritual, risking beaching themselves to catch seals and sea lions. These waters are also home to Chilean sea bass, albatross, and Magellanic penguins.
fields.title: Patagonia

fields.description: September 20, 2005—Katrina was perhaps the most destructive hurricane in U.S. history. How did it form?
fields.title: How Hurricane Katrina Formed

fields.description: January 10, 2013—A National Geographic explorer discovers what lies in a virtually untouched region on the eastern slopes of the Mauna Kea volcano in Hawaii.
fields.title: Hawaii's Hidden Paradise

fields.description: Photographer Danny Lyon's work captures some of the American Civil Rights Movement’s most compelling moments, from the March on Washington to the aftermath of the 16th Street Baptist Church bombing in Birmingham, Alabama. Lyon joined Civil Rights leader and politician Julian Bond for a wide-ranging conversation at the 2014 National Geographic Photography Seminar in Washington, D.C. This video is an excerpt of their discussion.Read more about their discussion at the seminar:http://proof.nationalgeographic.com/2014/01/20/civil-rights-photography-a-conversation-with-danny-lyon-and-julian-bond/Explore a gallery of Danny Lyon's photographs here:http://www.ethertongallery.com/exhibitions/lyon/show.html
fields.title: Photographing the Civil Rights Movement

fields.description: August 4, 2011—NASA's Juno spacecraft is headed on a five-year journey  to the solar system's largest planet, Jupiter. Along the way, the probe  will use Earth to "slingshot" itself toward the gas giant planet.
fields.title: NASA Probe to Explore Jupiter

fields.description: October 23, 2008—NASA's new prototype lunar rover improves on the original moon buggies by incorporating 35 years of technology, including an anti-rollover mechanism used in SUVs.

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans is traveling from Washington D.C. to Antarctica by bus, and in this video he makes a stop in Costa Rica's Corcovado National Park.

fields.title: Hawaii: Greening Army

fields.description: October 30, 2007—Astronauts install a solar power tower on the International Space Station and consider extending their mission.
fields.title: Astronauts Install New Tower

fields.description: How does augmented reality allow you to see around corners and behind walls? Learn more about this incredible science that blurs the line between the real world and the virtual.
fields.title: Augmented Reality

fields.description: It's the coldest, largest desert of the world, but in growing numbers, tourists are making their way to Antarctica.
fields.title: Destination: Antarctica

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler Contributing Editor Andrew Evans confesses to a childhood obsession with visiting the seals at the zoo. He got to spend some quality time with several species while visiting the South Orkney Islands in Antarctica.
fields.title: Seals the Deal

fields.description: After years of controversy, British Columbia has created the Great Bear Rainforest, a national park that protects part of the only temperate rain forest in the world.
fields.title: Vancouver Rain Forest

fields.description: Jodi Cobb describes the secrecy of a geisha's life.
fields.title: Geisha's Lips

fields.description: Wild Detectives investigates the legend of the giant pig monster named Hogzilla.
fields.title: Hogzilla

fields.description: October 23, 2007—The space shuttle Discovery launched Tuesday from Cape Canaveral, Florida, on a mission to expand the International Space Station.
fields.title: Shuttle Discovery Launches

fields.description: High in the Andes, an ancient Inca city flourished and was subsequently abandoned, lost to the outside world for centuries. Why was it built and deserted?
fields.title: The Mystery of Machu Picchu

fields.description: At first glance, this temple in northern India looks like any other. But this temple also houses other deities. And there's not one...not two...but over 15,000 of them inside. Welcome to the rat temple.
fields.title: Rat Temple

fields.description: Some favorite people photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: People

fields.description: October 14, 2009—For the first time, spacecraft have observed eruptions on the sun from multiple angles for hours on end—a feat made possible by NASA's twin STEREO craft.
fields.title: Solar Eruptions Captured in 3-D

fields.description: Discover why woodpeckers are hiding thousands of acorns.
fields.title: Acorn Stash

fields.description: Naturalists and guests on a National Geographic Expeditions cruise in Antarctica witness and record the phenomenon of Type B Orcas working in unison to dislodge a seal from an iceberg.
fields.title: Killer Whales "Gang Up" to Capture Seal

fields.description: The waters around Bermuda host a liquid jungle of creatures that exist in floating forests of golden brown sargassum seaweed. Deep within its waters live bioluminescent deep-sea creatures, reminiscent of comets, suns, and stars. Narrated by National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Sylvia Earle.
fields.title: Bermuda

fields.description: Altitude sickness, dueling ventilation systems, popped tires and more awaited National Geographic Contributing editor Andrew Evans as he boarded his bus to travel to Bolivia.
fields.title: Bus2Bolivia

fields.description: Learn the secrets of a private bear society in Alaska.
fields.title: Bear Meeting

fields.description: Wildlife photographer Steve Winter combines patience and groundbreaking technology to photograph North America's elusive and nocturnal big cat.The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.
fields.title: NG Live!: Cougars: From the Mountains to Hollywood

fields.description: April  5, 2011---Scientists are experimenting with "green" microbes in the lab that could someday be used to  gobble up oil spills along coastlines without damaging the environment.
fields.title: Oil-Eating Bacteria Engineered

fields.description: Andrew visits Kangaroo Island, Australia, and gets some hands-on experience with the island's namesake.
fields.title: Where's Andrew? My First Few Kangaroos

fields.description: Emerging Explorer Alexandra Cousteau examines the pollution problems of the Ganges from human and industrial waste.
fields.title: Ganges: Endangered Source

fields.description: August 5, 2013—The Smithsonian Institution's Museum of Natural History has started the largest biorepository in the world. It stores frozen specimens from hundreds of thousands of plant and animal species, primarily for genomic research.
fields.title: DNA and "Life on Ice"

fields.description: May 31, 2012—Scientists in Switzerland have developed a method to help paralyzed rats with severed spinal cords walk—and even climb stairs—again. The team's cocktail of neuronactivating chemicals and electrical stimulation might be a precursor to future treatments for disabled humans, researchers say.
fields.title: Paralyzed Rats Walk Again

fields.description: August 19, 2010—Hurricane Katrina devastated U.S. Gulf Coast communities five years ago, leaving behind ruins that persist to this day. But at least one of Mother Nature's iconic creations survived intact, and still inspires.
fields.title: 5 Years After Katrina, Ruins—And a Natural Wonder—Remain

fields.description: Watch this video with your family and friends to learn small steps that have a big impact on the well-being of our oceans.
fields.title: How to Care for the Ocean

fields.description: Glaciers on the Antarctic Peninsula are melting away at an alarming rate.
fields.title: Antarctica Ice

fields.description: October 22, 2009—In the wilds of northern Minnesota, bear expert Lynn Rogers teaches participants at a "wild encounters" education camp about bear language, manners, and lifestyle—all while getting up close and personal with wild black bears.
fields.title: How to Get Close to Wild Bears

fields.description: July 19, 2007—Archaeologists uncover and examine the 500-year-old skeleton of the Inca man they believe was the first shooting victim in the Americas.
fields.title: First New World Gunshot Victim Discovered

fields.description: Enjoy this rare archival glimpse into the preparations for Roald Amundsen's successful south pole expedition.
fields.title: Amundsen's South Pole Expedition

fields.description: A few members of the Ocean Now team spent the afternoon shooting locations on Cocos for a documentary that will be made about the expedition.
fields.title: Island of Waterfalls

fields.description: White pox is wiping out the elkhorn coral. And the disease may be coming from people.
fields.title: Elkhorn Coral

fields.description: Some favorite humor photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Laugh Track

fields.description: Some favorite eye photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Eye Spy

fields.description: July 9, 2009—Two years after most of Russia's geysers were lost in a landslide, a peculiar geyser has emerged on the Kamchatka Peninsula that spouts water every 6 to 20 minutes.
fields.title: New Geyser Erupts

fields.description: A brother and sister team complete the first-ever trek across the Northwest Passage on kite-skis.
fields.title: First Kite-Ski Trek across Arctic

fields.description: May 21, 2009—In and around Australia's Great Barrier Reef, researchers with the Census of Marine Life have discovered hundreds of new species.
fields.title: New Species Found at Great Barrier

fields.description: February 29, 2008—The "ice" part of the land of fire and ice—the glaciers—are in trouble. The story is part of the Wild Chronicles series Climate Connections.
fields.title: Iceland Melting?

fields.description: October 12, 2011—U.S. First Lady Michelle Obama helped kick off an  attempt to break a Guinness World Record for the most people doing a  minute's worth of jumping jacks in a 24-hour period. The attempt was  organized by National Geographic Kids. © 2011 National Geographic
fields.title: Jumping Jacks Record Sought

fields.description: October 8, 2009—Giant, jelly-like sheets of dead and living organic matter, known as marine mucilages, are spreading throughout the Mediterranean. The blobs may smother marine life and carry diseases dangerous to humans.
fields.title: Sea"Mucus" Blobs Pose Threat

fields.description: More favorite people photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Everyday People

fields.description: August 16, 2012—Researchers at Harvard University have created a flexible robot that can change colors to hide from animals and people. The camouflaging system may be useful in studying animal behavior and other subjects where stealth is an advantage.
fields.title: Rubber Robot Can Change Colors

fields.description: Andrew Evans takes a hot air balloon ride on his first day in Melbourne, Australia.
fields.title: Ballooning over Melbourne

fields.description: November 30, 2012—Want to reach a ripe old age? Hear what tips National Geographic Fellow Dan Buettner has gleaned from years researching Blue Zones, areas in the world where people live exceptionally long.
fields.title: How to Live to 100

fields.description: June 27, 2008—Copious chemicals and plastic make conventional banana growing far from "green." But a remote university is producing eco-friendly bananas that may be in your local grocery.
fields.title: Taking A Bite Out of Banana Mess

fields.description: For millennia, indigenous groups here have used plant hallucinogens in an ancient form of healing.  But can powerful drugs used as sacraments be taken by tourists, with the same mystical effects?
fields.title: Drug Tourists

fields.description: A slipper lobster has a protective shell, and it doesn't have to surface for air, but those advantages aren't enough to protect it from the powerful jaws of a loggerhead turtle.
fields.title: Loggerhead vs. Lobster

fields.description: Wild Detectives solves the mystery of why Rio the Parrot has a sudden change of heart.
fields.title: Rio the Parrot

fields.description: The Costa Rican coast guard calls with news: They've discovered illegal fishing lines in protected waters just a few miles from Cocos Island-something that happens with alarming (and increasing) frequency. The team hurries out, and is dismayed by what they find.
fields.title: A Lethal Web

fields.description: Easily mistaken for a sponge when standing still, this frogfish--a favorite of the Ocean Now expedition team--waddles the seafloor beneath Chatham Bay off Costa Rica's Cocos Island.
fields.title: Frogfish Blues

fields.description: World fish stocks may run out by 2048, reveals a new report from Science Magazine.
fields.title: Declining Fish

fields.description: February 1, 2010—The vampire squid can turn itself "inside out" to avoid predators. This new video was released by the Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute to emphasize the need to protect species like this in the deep oceans from the effects of human activities.
fields.title: Vampire Squid Turns "Inside Out"

fields.description: July 19, 2013—Robotics expert and National Geographic Emerging Explorer Chad Jenkins says that coming breakthroughs in robotics will soon make robots a bigger part of everyday life, helping us perform more tasks in our homes and workplaces.
fields.title: Can Robots Learn to Be More Human?

fields.description: Feb. 3, 2014—The biggest fireworks day in the U.S. is the Fourth of July. But the Chinese New Year is a time for fireworks, too. A New York fireworks company makes some special arrangements for the celebration.
fields.title: Chinese New Year Fireworks

fields.description: July 20, 2009—The total solar eclipse on Wednesday, July 22, 2009 will be the longest solar eclipse of the 21st century. Preview the eclipse via animations and more.
fields.title: Longest Solar Eclipse Coming

fields.description: Brothers Timmy and Sean O'Neill are not only a tight climbing team, but they have broken new ground for paraplegic climbers. Sean is paralyzed from the waist down after an accident years ago, but he and Timmy are scaling new heights. They climb the 3,000-foot wall of El Capitan in Yosemite, as well as a thousand-foot wall in the glaciated Ruth Gorge of Alaska.
fields.title: Brothers Wild: Timmy and Sean O'Neill

fields.description: While waiting for the seas to calm down so that his bus could pass the Straight of Magellan, National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans sips Mate with his fellow passengers, and enjoys the Argentine pastime of passing time.
fields.title: Mate - The Argentine Pastime of Passing Time

fields.description: Using tools like treadmills and wicked math problems, these scientists are on a mission to prove that stress isn't all in your mind. Join them on an incredible hunt for the sources of stress.
fields.title: Science of Stress

fields.description: June 16, 2009—A bug-eyed salamander and a colorful poison frog are among 12 species possibly new to science recently found in the mountains of Ecuador.
fields.title: 'Ugly' Salamander, New Frog Found

fields.description: National Geographic Traveler contributing editor Andrew Evans takes a icy dip in the waters off of Antarctica's Deception Island.
fields.title: An Antarctic Dip

fields.description: March 13, 2009—In researching sea turtles in Australia, National Geographic's Crittercam researchers discovered a surprise in the eating habits of the marine creatures.
fields.title: Turtle-Cam Shows Jellyfish Lunch

fields.description: January 29, 2007—Find out why peace remains an elusive dream for Somalia.
fields.title: Somalia: Behind the Headlines

fields.description: Up to 9 feet (2.7 meters) long and 300 pounds (136.1 kilograms), Pink River Dolphins are the largest freshwater dolphins in the world.
fields.title: Pink River Dolphins

fields.description: April 9, 2010, 2010—New National Geographic Crittercam footage shows never before seen eating habits of the Australian sea lion—including video of a sea lion hunting a large octopus. The footage is from a project intended to help save the endangered sea lions, in part by uncovering where and how the animals eat.
fields.title: Octopus vs. Sea Lion—First Ever Video

fields.description: February 13, 2008—Atlantis Astronauts conduct the second of three planned space walks, this one to install the International Space Station's new nitrogen tank.
fields.title: Astronauts on 2nd Space Walk

fields.description: Are you happy? Thrive author Dan Buettner suggests simple things   you can do right now to bring more fulfillment into your life. Today’s   tip: Volunteer.
fields.title: Volunteer

fields.description: Wandering Peru’s capital city, Andrew Evans stopped in Miguel Grau Park in the neighborhood of Miraflores. There, he found an incredible view of the Pacific Ocean and open-access skate park that was busy with some serious skateboarding and freestyle biking. "Maybe it’s because I’m traveling to Antarctica primarily on wheels, but I had to stop and catch the some of the ramp and half-pipe action," he says. "I snatched this quick video so that you skaters out there know what you’re up against in Lima."

fields.description: Some favorite colorful photos by National Geographic readers.
