fields.description: Meet a detective who swims with great white sharks.
fields.title: Great White Shark Detective

fields.description: Paul Nicklen describes his most amazing experience as a National Geographic photographer - coming face-to-face with one of Antarctica's most vicious predators.
fields.title: Face-Off With a Deadly Predator

fields.description: Young men from the Bessoribe tribe in Benin gather to get their skin sliced. This arduous, bloody process is a rite of manhood.
fields.title: Scarification

fields.description: February 25, 2008—An activist uses a video camera to expose what many would consider a grisly illegal wildlife trade in Myanmar. Warning: graphic imagery.
fields.title: Grisly Wildlife Trade Exposed

fields.description: November 22, 2009—A football octopod and a piglet squid are just a few of the bizarre deep-sea creatures uncovered during the ten-year Census of Marine Life, which ends in 2010.
fields.title: Piglet Squid, Other Bizarre Species Found

fields.description: Listen to the long-distance calls of elephants.
fields.title: Eavesdrop on Elephants

fields.description: Some favorite baby photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Raising Baby

fields.description: March 11, 2008—NASA's first nighttime launch since 2006 sent Endeavour on a 16-day space station mission. Astronauts will install a Canadian robot and a Japanese storage unit.
fields.title: Rare Nighttime Shuttle Launch

fields.description: How we taste and enjoy food is largely based on our sense of smell. Richard Ambrose and Jonny Phillips conduct a taste test while plugging their noses, as well as present their own flavored potato chips to a panel of professional food tasters.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Food Tasters

fields.description: When National Geographic Traveler contributing editor landed on Port Lockroy along the Antarctic Peninsula, he was surprised to befriend two Gentoo penguins who climbed into his lap.
fields.title: Close Encounters

fields.description: February 15, 2008—Astronauts installed a sun-monitoring device during the final space walk of the shuttle Atlantis's mission to deliver the Columbus lab to the Space Station.
fields.title: Spacewalkers Outfit New Lab

fields.description: December 20, 2006—Some of the world's great war photographers bear witness to the carnage in Darfur with a traveling exhibition of stunning images.
fields.title: Sudan: The Witness

fields.description: Alex Honnold makes the first free solos of the largest walls in North America. He scales 2,000 feet with only shoes and chalk bag—no rope, no safety, and no room for error. Though he's a superhero on the walls, off the rock Alex is a shy, self-effacing young guy living in his van. He's sort of a Clark Kent-Superman character.
fields.title: Alone on the Wall: Alex Honnold

fields.description: In Papua New Guinea, a group of initiates is about to enter the final stage of a long and arduous ritual. There is no set age for the rite ... but no one can have full status as a man until he's been scarred with the mark of the crocodile.
fields.title: Crocodile Scars

fields.description: Discover why monk seals in Hawaii like to go around flipping rocks.
fields.title: Monk Seals

fields.description: December 23, 2013—With its long, curved horns, the scimitar-horned oryx is one of the most interesting of the cow relatives. After years of declining numbers, scientists have successfully bred the African animal in captivity, giving hope for the species' long-term survival in the wild.
fields.title: Scimitar-Horned Oryx Making a Comeback

fields.description: Creating stunning, cutting-edge adventure films hasn’t gotten any easier. There’s still plenty of sweat and swearing. It has gotten a little cheaper, and, with YouTube, a viral video is only a few clicks away. Filmmaker and adventurer Bryan Smith has been at the forefront of this grassroots movement
fields.title: Filmmaking: Adventure Vision

fields.description: Canada, 2011, 4 minutesProduced by: Patrick CamblinDirected by: Patrick Camblin / Tribe AllianceWebsite: www.triberiders.caClassification: GeneralSome of the world's best kayakers come together for a six stage competition on spectacular whitewater.
fields.title: Radical Reels: Whitewater Grand Prix

fields.description: May 22, 2008—Across the globe, skyrocketing food prices are inciting riots, hoarding, and starvation. What has caused the worst food crisis in a generation?
fields.title: World Food in Crisis

fields.description: The Global Partnership for Oceans is a growing alliance of governments, international organizations, civil society groups, and private sector interests committed to addressing the threats to the health, productivity and resilience of the world's oceans.
fields.title: The Global Partnership for Oceans

fields.description: A high-speed camera captures the cat’s two-second sprint in slow motion, revealing every stride.
fields.title: The World’s Fastest Runner

fields.description: See what happens in pitch-black caves, using cool thermal cameras.
fields.title: Caught on Camera

fields.description: Hundreds of thousands of Shia Muslims live in Hyderabad, India...and for several days each year, they demonstrate their faith in a dramatic spectacle called Matam.
fields.title: Matam

fields.description: On a sunny afternoon in August, Dean Potter stepped onto a tongue of rock just below the summit of Switzerland’s Eiger and jumped off. At first he plunged toward a ledge 600 feet below, then air gathered in his wingsuit, his forward trajectory kicked in, and he began to fly. By the time he pulled his chute and drifted to earth, Potter had spent two minutes and 50 seconds in flight. It was the longest BASE jump ever, covering some 9,000 vertical feet and nearly four miles.
fields.title: Fly or Die: Dean Potter

fields.description: October 9, 2009—NASA's "moon bombing" Friday morning was successful, but the LCROSS impact proved anticlimatic to many skywatchers.
fields.title: LCROSS Impact Video: No Sky Show

fields.description: October 29, 2007—Astronauts break in the new addition to the International Space Station, conduct a second space walk, and plan for a third.
fields.title: Module Added to Space Station

fields.description: A desperately hungry Vumbi lion pride successfully captures a warthog from its den, and a feeding frenzy ensues.
fields.title: From Famine to Feast

fields.description: Some favorite sports photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Game's People Play

fields.description: March 10, 2008—Watch as a scientist uncovers tiny human bones in a tropical island cave, in what could be a major discovery.
fields.title: Ancient Little People Found?

fields.description: Superclimber Alex Honnold zips up the face of El Capitan.
fields.title: Going Vertical With Alex Honnold

fields.description: It's the most unholy of acts—drinking human blood. Committed by creatures of the night—vampires! Most people don't think they really exist. But could it be they're closer than you'd ever dream?
fields.title: Vampires

fields.description: In rural Ethiopia, the old ways still prevail. 25 miles from Addis Ababa, the village of Debre Zeyet prepares for a special ritual. From miles around, the ill and the injured come—hoping to see the one person they believe can help.
fields.title: Healing Spirit

fields.description: Help Puff, a tiny seal pup, find her missing mother.
fields.title: Puff's Mom

fields.description: Some favorite on-the-job photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: On the Job

fields.description: Some favorite summertime photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Summer's End

fields.description: Explore the many types of octopuses.
fields.title: Octopuses

fields.description: In 1418, Filippo Brunelleschi was tasked with building the largest dome ever seen at the time. He had no formal architecture training. Yet experts still don’t fully understand the brilliant methods he used in contructing the dome, which tops the Santa Maria del Fiore cathedral in Florence, Italy.
fields.title: How an Amateur Built the World’s Biggest Dome

fields.description: Canada, 2011, 7 minutesProduced and directed by: Darren Rayner, Callum Jelley, and Mason MashonWebsite: www.voleurz.comClassification: General - Coarse LanguageShot and edited in only seven days, discover the true meaning of cat skiing!
fields.title: Radical Reels: Cat Skiing

fields.description: Some favorite storm photos by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: Stormy Weather

fields.description: The National Geographic Live! series brings thought-provoking presentations by today’s leading explorers, scientists, photographers, and performing artists right to your YouTube feed. Each presentation is filmed in front of a live audience at National Geographic headquarters in Washington, D.C. New clips air every Monday.In the kickoff to one of the year's most highly anticipated events—National Geographic's Explorer's Symposium—join some of the world's top explorers as they share their work in the field ... and the tales of adventure, danger, and discovery that go along with it. (Participants: Photographers and filmmakers Joel Sartore and Sandesh Kadur; planetary geologist Bethany Ehlmann; and anthropologist Jason De León).
fields.title: NG Live!: A New Age of Exploration

fields.description: Dive alongside blue whales and crack their secret code of communication.
fields.title: Crack the Blue Whale Code

fields.description: January 5, 2010—Built to rove for 90 days, Spirit has lasted six years on Mars. But now it's stuck and may lose power by May. Even standing still, though, Spirit can do a surprising amount of science, NASA says.
fields.title: Stuck Mars Rover About to Die?

fields.description: January 25, 2008—A herd of hippos once owned by Pablo Escobar, Colombia's famed drug lord, run free on Escobar's former estate—creating a problem for the government.
fields.title: Drug Lord's Hippos Thriving

fields.description: Digital Nomad Andrew Evans finds himself on the most remote inhabited island in the world during a devastating oil spill.
fields.title: NG Live!: Tristan da Cunha Oil Spill

fields.description: April 16, 2008—National Geographic producer Michael Davie was an eyewitness to yesterday's plane crash in Goma that reportedly killed at least 21 people.
fields.title: Eyewitness to Congo Crash

fields.description: August 13, 2009—NASA helicopters have lowered about a dozen monitoring "spiders" in and around Mount St. Helens's volcanic crater to better predict major eruptions.
fields.title: NASA Drops "Spiders" Into Volcano

fields.description: The human body performs amazing feats every day, from sending signals rocketing through the brain at high speed to distributing oxygen over 1,000 miles (1,600 kilometers) of airways.
fields.title: Human Body 101

fields.description: July 6, 2011---Sea turtle nesting season is underway on Gulf of Mexico  beaches, and observers say activity seems normal. But these aren't the  same animals that nested during last year's Gulf oil spill, and  scientists are concerned about a continued rise in turtle deaths.
fields.title: Gulf Turtle Nests Abound, But Worries Remain

fields.description: When National Geographic Explorer Shannon Switzer's friends started getting sick from surfing, the pollution problem in her area became personal. Find out how she's educating the public in order to protect our waters.
fields.title: Explorer: Shannon Switzer

fields.description: This alpha male gelada doesn't want to cede control of his harem to a band of bachelors. So he'll pull out all the stops. But will it be enough?
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Gelada vs. Gelada

fields.description: Young Explorer and wildlife biologist Eric Patterson swims with a group of dolphins that have developed an unusual and intelligent hunting strategy. See what he and his crew have discovered in Shark Bay, Australia.
fields.title: Why Dolphins Use Tools

fields.description: With keen eyesight, excellent hearing, and sensitive motion detectors, this great white shark is locked and loaded. Nearby seals are agile and alert, but they'll have to move fast.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Great White Shark vs. Seals

fields.description: Capable of diving at 60 miles per hour, cape gannets are nature's missiles. They're just as deadly underwater, where they can pursue prey at depths of up to 40 feet.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: "Missile" Birds

fields.description: National Geographic Young Explorer and marine biologist, Eric Patterson uses a new and non-invasive method to test dolphin health at the National Aquarium.
fields.title: Breathing Knowledge

fields.description: Watch how National Geographic Magazine photographers and editors mentor young people around the world to learn how to express themselves and engage with their communities though the art of photography.
fields.title: National Geographic Photo Camp Overview

fields.description: January 26, 2012—Researchers have discovered a unique visual attribute that jumping spiders use in attacking and catching prey. The arachnids use what is called image defocus-proven in part by videos that show spiders jumping with deadly accuracy in green light (and fumbling in red).
fields.title: Spiders Jump With Deadly Accuracy in Green Light - TEST - 2200

fields.description: Who needs text messages? Dolphins have weird communications on lockdown, from blowing bubbles to swimming in-synch.
fields.title: Dolphin Talk Decoded

fields.description: The Portuguese man-of-war is 50 times bigger than this nudibranch, a tiny sea slug. But in this David-versus-Goliath scenario, don't bet against the nudibranch. It can nibble away at its enemy's deadly tentacles and use the man-of-war's stingers for its own.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Amazing Sting Defense

fields.description: California, a leading state in solar power, has found many ways to harness the Sun, the most powerful source of energy on the planet. Cities, such as Sacramento, are working to make solar power competitively priced and reliable with bulk use of solar cells and solar panels. California offers its citizens net metering, the option to sell solar power back to utilities and to earn money. In the Mojave Desert, Kramer Junction, a solar power facility, also creates an impressive amount of power.
fields.title: Solar Power

fields.description: Explorer and biologist Karen DeMatteo has a difficult job—searching for elusive and endangered species of wild cats and dogs. Her best tool? An obsessive dog with a fantastic nose. DeMatteo's Chesapeake lab, Train, has a deep fixation for chasing his tennis ball, and she has harnessed that obsessive energy for a scientific purpose—sniffing out five species of animal scat in the forests of Misiones, Argentina. Finding the scat helps her know how the animals use their habitat and therefore how to protect them.
fields.title: A Dog's Nose for Conservation

fields.description: Meet the little red flying fox, a bat with a wingspan of up to three feet. Its wings take a lot of work to maintain - and one missed approach while getting a drink can land this bat in the mouth of a crocodile.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Flying Foxes

fields.description: Painted dogs are ruthless killers when they team up against large prey. But they show surprising compassion at home, sharing food with the old and sick.
fields.title: Killer Caretakers: Painted Dogs

fields.description: Houseflies regurgitate on food to tenderize it, spreading harmful bacteria from their previous meals. And their squirming offspring aren't much better company ... although they do play a vital role as nature's recyclers.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Flies and Maggots

fields.description: When it comes to feeding, this thumb-sized bat definitely sides with Dracula. Vampire bats are the only mammals on an all-blood diet — and an unsuspecting cow is the perfect prey.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Vampire Bats

fields.description: An osprey mom, named Rachel, feeds some freshly caught fish to her just-hatched babies atop her nest at the Audubon Camp on Hog Island, Maine. Ospreys rely almost entirely on fish for food, so the nest is near the water. Ospreys mate for life, and Rachel's partner, named Steve, also appears in this video, helping mom raise the chicks.
fields.title: Feeding Time

fields.description: A narwhal's tusk makes it weird among whales. It's actually a tooth that can reach ten feet in length, and scientists have numerous theories about its powers and purpose.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Narwhals

fields.description: Grizzly bears can and will eat just about anything. And that means running down whatever they can catch, from elk calves and salmon to baby bison.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Grizzly Bear Attacks Prey

fields.description: Bald eagle chicks, which hatched in this nest in March 2013, move about their nest. They're awaiting their parents' return with fish caught from the nearby Anacostia River. The chicks are covered with black juvenile feathers.
fields.title: Bald Eagle Webcam Chicks

fields.description: The Portuguese man-of-war is a superorganism, a colony of tiny animals that form a very menacing predator.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Portuguese Man-of-War

fields.description: Custom mountain bikes are fast, tough, and expensive. Go behind the scenes and watch dedicated builders meticulously assemble and test bikes for world champion riders.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Building a Mountain Bike

fields.description: Amy Dickman—a National Geographic Big Cats Initiative grantee—thanks you for your support of Nat Geo's work in the field.To support the work of National Geographic, please visit nationalgeographic.org/donate.
fields.title: Big Cats Initiative Grantee Amy Dickman Thanks Nat Geo

fields.description: Eight legs and sticky webs might seem like an advantage in this fight. But will it be enough to keep this spider from becoming a meal for the wasp's ravenous young?
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Hairy Spider vs. Wasp

fields.description: In incredible footage, an African rock python swallows a springbok antelope. It has jaws designed to engulf meals three times bigger than its head.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Python Eats Antelope

fields.description: This Galápagos hawk has a ferocious takedown strategy: sinking sharp talons into an iguana's head. But the fight is far from over.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Hawk Attacks Iguana

fields.description: They might look cute and cuddly, but at dinnertime these meerkats form a menacing mob. They team up to dig for scorpions, whose stings have no effect on them.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Meerkat Mob

fields.description: Bald eagle parents feed chicks in their nest in Washington, DC after they catch fish from the nearby Anacostia River. The chicks, which hatched in March 2013, are covered with black juvenile feathers.
fields.title: Bald Eagle Webcam Feeding

fields.description: This edited version of a declassified U.S. Navy training film from 1945 shows how balloon bombs were created and launched from Japan to land and detonate in North America.
fields.title: Declassifed Navy Film Shows Balloon Bomb

fields.description: Their bloody appetite is no Halloween myth. Vampire bats use sonar and their sensitive ears to search for prey in dense cover. With a target acquired, superpowered noses help them locate blood beneath a peccary's skin ... and the feast begins.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Vampire Bats

fields.description: When this poisonous monarch comes out to hunt, the whole forest steers clear. That is, until a rat snake blunders into its path ... and gets swallowed alive!
fields.title: World's Deadliest: King Cobra

fields.description: It's no mythical monster. When threatened, this real-life lizard can glide half the length of a football field ... and still swoop in for a perfect landing.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Flying Dragon

fields.description: Researchers have found that elephants have hundreds of distinct signals and gestures. Elephant biologist and conservationist Joyce Poole and her husband, Petter Granli, founders of ElephantVoices, developed an online database of those signals, as described in an article on National Geographic's A Voice for Elephants blog. Among the categories of signals and gestures is "play." Watch a video of elephants at play as Joyce Poole narrates and explains their behavior.
fields.title: Elephants Communicate While at Play

fields.description:
Our investigation is revealing insights into the ivory trade, which is causing elephant numbers to fall to lower levels than ever recorded. An international ban on trading ivory has been in place since 1989. But since then, the international body that governs the trade, known as CITES, has allowed two large auctions of stockpiled ivory.
Our cameras were allowed into a luxury goods store showroom in Beijing, where Bryan Christy explains how those auctions complicate what's for sale legally and what's not.
Battle for the Elephants airs February 27th at 9PM on PBS. Check local listings.
fields.title: Battle for the Elephants Episode 3: The China Ivory Market

fields.description: See what kids and adults say about Meerkats 3D!
fields.title: Audience Reactions—Meerkats 3D

fields.description: Battle for the Elephants explores the brutal slaughter of African elephants for their tusks, fueled largely by China's demand for ivory. Premieres Wednesday, February 27, 2013, on PBS. Check local listings.
fields.title: Battle for the Elephants: Preview

fields.description: A selection of our favorite light photos submitted to My Shot by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: MY SHOT Minute - Light Motif

fields.description: A selection of our favorite reptile photos submitted to My Shot by National Geographic readers.
fields.title: MY SHOT Minute - Reptiles

fields.description: Watch as a bearded seal pup wearing a National Geographic Crittercam interacts with her mother in waters near Norway.  Listen carefully as you can hear the pup communicating. POV video is from the "Point of View" of the animal on which it is attached as part of the Crittercam research program. They're presented by popular demand from those who want to see more POV footage than appears in other Crittercam videos.
fields.title: Crittercam POV: Seal Mom & Pup

fields.description: It has a big, bulbous head...beady black eyes...and eight squirming tentacles. It's the octopus. Many would call it ugly and disgusting. The one thing they wouldn't call it is dinner.
fields.title: The Ultimate Raw Fish

fields.description: Take advantage of a few simple accessories to make shooting HD video with your DSLR look flawless and fun.
fields.title: DSLR HD Video Tips: Accessories

fields.description: Join chef and National Geographic Fellow Barton Seaver on the shores of the Chesapeake Bay, where he meets a father-son crab-fishing team working to keep a family business and a local tradition alive.
fields.title: 'B' the Recipe

fields.description: Once plentiful, can Chesapeake Bay oysters make a comeback? Chef and National Geographic Fellow Barton Seaver visits the owners of hundred-year-old oyster company who are working to keep the famous oysters on the map—and on our plates. Learn how farming helps restore oyster populations, then follow Seaver’s easy recipe for grilled oysters.
fields.title: Environmentalism on the Half Shell

fields.description: The National Geographic All Roads Film Project, the Diversity Development department of FOX Entertainment Group, and the Native Media and Technology Network are the three partners behind the American Indian Summer Institute (AISI), a series of professional workshops held every summer in Los Angeles, California.  This year’s institute attendees produced public-service announcements (PSAs) with an environmental theme.
fields.title: 2010 AISI PSAs

fields.description: See professional kayaker Tyler Bradt set a new world record paddling 186  feet (57 meters) over Palouse Falls in eastern Washigton.
fields.title: Kayak Waterfall Record

fields.description: Travel by air with Mike Fay across Africa as he takes detailed digital still images of the continent to examine the human footprint on the land.
fields.title: Africa Megaflyover

fields.description: If trekking 485 miles (781 kilometers)  is not an option, focus on the  trail’s best 68 miles (109 kilometers)  between San Luis Pass and Molas  Pass.
fields.title: Hiking the Colorado Trail

fields.description: Join National Geographic photographer Mark Thiessen on the front line of one of nature's fiercest forces.
fields.title: Fighting Wildfires

fields.description: Ma di Tau, star of The Last Lions movie, is built to kill, but she faces  a gauntlet of enemies — buffalo, hyenas, and even the other lions who  would kill her cubs — and it's a fight to the death.
fields.title: Lioness vs. Buffalo

fields.description: Holy Crap! is a documentary film about how human waste is creating a bright new future for Haiti. Asks how First World issues might be addressed by a similar process.
fields.title: Holy Crap!

fields.description: Emerging Explorer Jerry Glover connects healthy soil to human survival.
fields.title: Jerry Glover, Agroecologist

fields.description: In  partnership with NOAA, Ocean for Life brought 30 students from all over the world  together to  learn about one another through ocean science, documenting  their  experience with the help of the National Geographic Photo Camp  Media Team. In this video the students poetically share what the overall Ocean for Life experience means to them.
fields.title: Ocean for Life-Overall Experience

fields.description: Emerging Explorer Emma Stokes learns a valuable lesson while camping in a forest in Congo.
fields.title: Emma Stokes, Conservationist and Wildlife Researcher

fields.description: Johnny Rooks usually prefer vulnerable chicks as a meal, but one ambitious group targets prey much larger than  themselves.
fields.title: Johnny Rooks Stalk Fur Seal Pup

fields.description: “Red Rain” from Peter Gabriel – New Blood Live In London courtesy of Eagle Rock Entertainment. Filmed at Hammersmith Apollo in March of this year, New Blood  Live In London captures Peter Gabriel performing live with the 46 piece New Blood Orchestra. The repertoire mixes cover versions from his “Scratch My Back” album with classic tracks from across his solo career in brand new orchestral arrangements.
fields.title: “Red Rain”  (New Blood Live In London)

fields.description: Explorers-in-Residence Mike Fay describes his feelings as he treks through the California redwood forest.
fields.title: Mike Fay, Conservationist

fields.description: On March 13, 2011, NG Explorers Andy Maser and Trip Jennings joined forces with Samuel Wasser to identify elephant poaching hotspots in the Democratic Republic of Congo.
fields.title: Elephant Ivory Project

fields.description: "It was at that moment that I realized that you could be a scientist while still doing crazy, extreme things and that's what I wanted to do."
fields.title: National Geographic Explorer: Albert Lin

fields.description: A snake bite in his youth cannot discourage Emerging Explorer Zoltan Takacs from pursuing dangerous and venomous vipers.
fields.title: Zoltan Takacs, Herpetologist and Toxinologist

fields.description: Emerging Explorer Feliciano dos Santos uses music to advocate for better sanitation.
fields.title: Feliciano dos Santos, Musician and Activist

fields.description: Backflips, ollies, and handplants...in a wheelchair? Meet young heroes who pursue their dreams in spite of challenging obstacles.  Teen athlete Patrick Ivison tells explore.org that the Life Rolls On Foundation "gives people who have kind of lost everything a chance to bring it all back."
fields.title: Life Rolls On

fields.description: These clams might not have a brain, but they do have a foot for digging. They'd better move quick, or these rays and birds will have them for dinner.
fields.title: Clams vs. the World

fields.description: The Teton County, Wyoming Search and Rescue Team and its K-9 rescue dogs perform a "live" rescue when a skier gets "trapped" in an avalanche and is buried alive. Every second counts in an avalanche rescue.
fields.title: Adrenaline Junkies: Avalanches and Rescues

fields.description: The Indian Red Scorpion is considered the most lethal of all scorpions.  But despite its reputation, it only stings as a last resort. And rather  than humans, it prefers to feast on insects, like roaches.
fields.title: World's Deadliest Scorpion?

fields.description: National Geographic Emerging Explorer Dr. Luke Dollar, a biologist, has  been returning to Madagascar for the past 17 years. Luke originally came  to study lemurs, but after his study animal was eaten by the island’s  top predator, the Fossa, Luke switched to studying these mysterious  cat-like animals. Madagascar’s forests, the fossa’s habitat, have  declined nearly 93%, with the remaining 7% under pressure from an  expanding human population. Luke’s hope is to find a sustainable balance  between the Malagasy people who depend on the forests, and the natural  species that live there.
fields.title: Preserving Madagascar’s Unique Species

fields.description: Disaster search dogs and their handlers save lives in times of crisis. Learn more about the foundation that takes the call to action.
fields.title: Disaster Search Dogs Save Lives

fields.description: Meet Jason O'Neill and his canine partner and learn how avalanche rescue dogs work their magic.
fields.title: Avalanche Search Dogs: Spaniel

fields.description: Meet environmentalist Juan Martinez, a National Geographic explorer who's trying to teach kids that it's cool to play in the dirt.
fields.title: Explorer: Juan Martinez

fields.description: Candles. Campfires. They give off beautiful golden light—but not very much. Here's how to capture both the flame and your subject.Like what you see? Get the complete Playing With Fire photo tip here.
fields.title: Playing With Fire

fields.description: It's not just a virtue, it's also a necessity for making good photographs—and you might even have some fun.Like what you see? Get the complete Patience photo tip here.
fields.title: Patience!

fields.description: This pack hunter is your own next-of-kin. But some of our closest cousins are killers who can eat up to a ton of meat in a year.
fields.title: Killers Like Us: Chimpanzees

fields.description: Legendary expert in the evolution of early man, Richard Leakey, introduces a 15 year old from 1.5 million years ago. Richard, his wife Meave and daughter Louise Leakey are long-time grantees of National Geographic. Bones of Turkana premieres on PBS May 16, 2012 at 10pm Eastern. Check local listings.
fields.title: Want to Meet Your Ancestors?

fields.description: Paul Simon's Under African Skies from the epic Graceland album provides the perfect score for the first few minutes of a new National Geographic Special on PBS - Bones of Turkana.
fields.title: Paul Simon Rocks Bones of Turkana

fields.description: A velvet worm might be nearly blind, but it's got a weapon: It can slime its prey from nearly a foot away, and paralyze it. The worm can shoot two sticky ropes up to a foot long that incapacitate unwary bugs, making them easy prey.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Bizarre Slime Cannon Attack

fields.description: Astronomers using NASA's Spitzer Space Telescope have detected what they believe is an alien world just two-thirds the size of Earth -- one of the smallest on record. The exoplanet candidate, known as UCF-1.01, orbits a star called GJ 436, which is located a mere 33 light-years away. UCF-1.01 might be the nearest world to our solar system that is smaller than our home planet.
fields.title: Exoplanet UCF-1.01 Orbits GJ 436

fields.description: Take a look at one Italian family's copy of "The Battle of Anghiari" and see what happens when the team runs into some problems in the Hall of 500.
fields.title: The Lost Leonardo: Deleted Scenes

fields.description: Humpback whales have a simple hunting strategy: blow bubbles, trap dinner at the surface... and open wide.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Giant Jaws of Death

fields.description: For flatworms, "Who's your daddy?" is a loaded question. In a bizarre bout lasting up to an hour, the first flatworm to stab and inseminate its mate becomes the father.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Flatworm Penis Fencing

fields.description: In Bracken Cave, TX, Batman would be seriously outnumbered. But can this swarm of millions of bats drive off the attack of a determined hunter, the hawk?
fields.title: Bats Swarm to Survive

fields.description: On April 15, 1912 the RMS Titanic tragically sunk to the bottom of the sea.  73 years later, National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Dr. Robert Ballard and his team discovered the famed liner's remains.  Watch Dr. Ballard describe how he gathered support to find the Titanic, the moment of its discovery and the mission to preserve its legacy.
fields.title: Titanic: A Remembrance

fields.description: The rough-skinned newt might look innocuous. But the newt's red underbelly means poison, and a frog is about to find out the hard way... by eating it.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Swallowed Newt Escapes Death

fields.description: The geothermal heat pump system is an energy-efficient heating and cooling alternative. It moves heat from the ground to a building, or from a building to the ground, through a series of flexible pipe "loops" containing water. This edition of Energy 101, from the U.S. Department of Energy, explores the benefits of geothermal and the science behind how it all comes together.
fields.title: Energy 101: Geothermal Heat Pumps

fields.description: Topping out at 10 feet in length, the one-ton leopard seal is Antarctica's top hunter. Any penguin that doesn't stay with the group risks becoming the seal's meal.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Seal vs. Penguin

fields.description: It might be a featherweight, but this tiny mantis shrimp packs a powerful punch. A crab tries to shield itself behind glass a quarter-inch thick ... but will it be enough to stop the hungry shrimp?
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Shrimp Packs a Punch

fields.description: The National Geographic Expeditions Council funds exploration in little-known areas of the planet, as well as regions undergoing significant change. Through our stories we hope to foster a deeper understanding of the world and its inhabitants.
fields.title: Exploration Without Limits

fields.description: You can't tell wild animals how to pose or when to show up for the best light. See why patience and silence pay off.Like what you see? Get the complete Shooting Wildlife photo tip here.
fields.title: Shooting Wildlife

fields.description: The 11-pound horse conch might seem invincible against most threats. But the tables are turned a bit when hermit crabs stage an invasion of the dinner-snatchers.
fields.title: Hermit Crab vs. Horse Conch

fields.description: Like scaly sumo wrestlers, these male monitor lizards are squaring off over food and females. They might brawl for 45 minutes before a victor emerges.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Lizard vs. Lizard

fields.description: For decades, the mighty Colorado River has been diverted to growing cities and farmland, halting the river's progress to the sea. Now with governments and environmental groups in the U.S. and Mexico working together, there is hope to once again connect the river to the sea.
fields.title: Returning the Colorado River to the Sea

fields.description: Young Explorer and photographer Anand Varma takes us to the end of the world—Patagonia, Chile—where he looks at the role of water in the landscape through experimental photography.
fields.title: Photography at the End of the World

fields.description: The underwater version of a tank, this cone snail boasts an armored shell and enough venom to kill a human. Nearby fish don't stand a chance.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Killer Cone Snail

fields.description: This shark's distinctive head is designed for greater agility and panoramic vision, making the hammerhead a hunter to be reckoned with.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Hammerhead Sharks

fields.description: Its saliva is loaded with venom and more than 50 strains of virulent bacteria—any animal it bites will likely die within days.
fields.title: World Weirdest: Toxic Dragon

fields.description: Travel to China to visit a factory that mass-produces the popular plastic Christmas tree for the Western market.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: How Christmas Trees Are Made

fields.description: Evolutionary biologists Nate Dappen and Neil Losin, a young explorer at National Geographic, work together studying lizards and reaching out to the world around them. As science communicators, they share a passion for nature through photography and filmmaking.
fields.title: Lizard Men

fields.description: With a quick snap of its claw, a pistol shrimp stuns prey with a "bubble bullet" that travels as fast as a car.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Amazing Pistol Shrimp Stun "Gun"

fields.description: Before taking thrill seekers on a heart-racing ride, a state-of-the-art roller coaster is rigorously tested every morning in order to be declared fit for use.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Roller Coaster Testing

fields.description: The male Mediterranean fruit fly secretes his cologne from a special place. The ladies love it ... but local predators also home in on the scent.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Smelly Fruit Fly Cologne

fields.description: Joel Sartore shares about the personal ins and outs of what it’s like to be the man behind the camera, as he travels the globe photographing people, habitats and animals.
fields.title: Joel Sartore: A Photographer's Life

fields.description: Beluga calves start their complex vocalizations within hours of being born. But all the whistling in the world can't save a baby who gets beached.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Baby Beluga Beached

fields.description: Before he can mate with a female, this young stallion has to prove he has the right stuff. He may need to fight off her dad.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Zebra vs. Zebra

fields.description: National Geographic Explorer Amy Dickman, one of Tanzania's most formidable big cat conservationists, is bringing the world closer to what she says is some of the most amazing wilderness left on Earth.
fields.title: Making Friends With Technology

fields.description: Meet a pest that can really get under your skin ... or in your head. The parasitic botfly lays its eggs in "vector hosts"—including humans. Removing the hungry larva can be awkward, painful, and downright disturbing.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Larva Removed From a Girl's Scalp

fields.description: In this scorpion standoff, the first one stung is immobilized ... and then devoured.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Cannibal Scorpions Fight to the Death

fields.description: The albatross has the biggest wingspan of any bird. But getting airborne takes some training ... and shark-infested waters demand a steep learning curve.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Albatross vs. Shark

fields.description: They don't walk, and they aren't really dead. But these snails are zombies. They have been hijacked by parasites that control their brains and movements. It's a clever ploy to help the parasites' offspring spread and endure.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Zombie Snails

fields.description: Bachelors beware! On a dinner date with a female black widow spider, the male can wind up becoming the main course.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Deadly Mating

fields.description: We've heard some crazy stories here at National Geographic—everything from a polar bear that shredded an occupied tent to a livid elephant that nearly gored a man. None so terrifying, however, than big cat biologist Amy Dickman's lion encounter ... but maybe not in the way you might think.
fields.title: Amy Dickman: Sleeping With Lions

fields.description: For the last 125 years, National Geographic has been on the cutting edge of adventure, science, technology and photography.  Discover how today’s National Geographic explorers are launching us into the next great age of exploration.
fields.title: National Geographic: Welcome to the New Age of Exploration

fields.description: Did you know that the t-shirt on your back has a major impact on the planet? Producing it took 2,700 liters of water, plus it takes a lot of energy to get it from the cotton fields to your closet.  But some of your t-shirt’s biggest impacts are in how you care for it. Here's how you can help reduce its effect on the environment.
fields.title: How Your T-Shirt Can Make a Difference

fields.description: Some highlight clips of bald eagle chicks, which hatched in this Washington, DC nest in March 2013, and their parents. The webcam is mounted in a nearby tree, which is why the camera is often moving: it's being blown by wind.
fields.title: Bald Eagle Webcam Highlights

fields.description: Take a "swim" with gray reef sharks in the Pacific Ocean, as seen with National Geographic's Crittercam. POV video is from the "Point of View" of the animal on which it is attached as part of a Crittercam research project. They're presented by popular demand from those who want to see more POV footage than appears in other Crittercam videos.
fields.title: Crittercam POV: "Swim" with Gray Reef Sharks

fields.description: A female black widow spider doesn't always kill her mate. But if he doesn't get away fast enough, she'll turn him into insect soup.
fields.title: Black Widow: Most Venomous Spider in North America

fields.description: A praying mantis is harmless to humans, but deadly to grasshoppers. And a mantis has its own predators to watch out for.
fields.title: Praying Mantis vs. Grasshopper

fields.description: Discover how the ocean influences a California vineyard and the sparkling wines it produces in this episode of Cook-Wise, featuring chef and conservationist Barton Seaver on location in Sonoma Valley.
fields.title: Wine From Water

fields.description: Watch as a young, female brown bear, wearing a National Geographic Crittercam, interacts with other brown bears: playing, grooming, and snoozing.   NOTE: the name "grizzly" is often incorrectly used for any brown bear, but grizzlies are just a regional type of brown bear. POV video is from the "Point of View" of the animal on which it is attached as part of the Crittercam research program. They're presented by popular demand from those who want to see more POV footage than appears in other Crittercam videos.
fields.title: Crittercam POV: Brown Bears Socializing

fields.description: The Striped Bass represents one of the greatest success stories we have in conservation to date. Join waterman Rick Morlock and the Blue Ocean Institute’s Carl Safina to discuss the phenomenon and catch a few beauties to grill up Seaver style.
fields.title: The Sweet Taste of Success

fields.description: Watch an Alaskan brown bear sample the rich forest vegetation before catching a tasty salmon meal. POV video is from the "Point of View" of the animal on which it is attached as part of the Crittercam research program. They're presented by popular demand from those who want to see more POV footage than appears in other Crittercam videos.
fields.title: Crittercam POV: Brown Bear Catches Salmon

fields.description: When researchers deployed a National Geographic Crittercam on female leatherback turtles, they hoped to learn whether they fed between nesting bouts. They don't. The females did spend time trying to avoid would-be suitors - males that no one had known were in the area. POV video is from the "Point of View" of the animal on which it is attached as part of the Crittercam research program. They're presented by popular demand from those who want to see more POV footage than appears in other Crittercam videos.
fields.title: Crittercam POV: Underwater Turtle Mating

fields.description: Learn how to make your HD videos look like a pro’s with tips and tricks for stabilizing your camera.
fields.title: DSLR HD Video Tips: Stabilizing the Camera

fields.description: Watch an Eastern Pacific Green Turtle, also called a Black Turtle because of its dark shell, forage in the Gulf of California. POV video is from the "Point of View" of the animal on which it is attached as part of the Crittercam research program. They're presented by popular demand from those who want to see more POV footage than appears in other Crittercam videos.
fields.title: Crittercam POV: "Black" Turtle

fields.description: Adventurer of the Year Francois Bon's unique pursuit of gravity.
fields.title: Speed Riding Aconcagua

fields.description: Connect the dots (six spare but well-outfitted  huts spaced  approximately 35 miles/56 kilometers apart) on a weeklong  mountain bike  expedition that starts in the jagged San Juan Mountains  and ends in  Moab. Harder and more isolated than its twin, the venerable   Telluride-Moab ride, the 215-mile (346-kilometer) Durango-Moab route   presents navigational and bike-handling challenges and a sense of  unfettered  freedom.
fields.title: Biking Durango to Moab

fields.description: In May 2010, Spanish mountaineer Edurne Pasaban completed a nine-year quest to climb the world’s 14 8,000-meter peaks, a feat which made her our People's Choice Adventurer of the Year.
fields.title: Edurne Pasaban: 2011 Adventurer of the Year

fields.description: The Southwest’s most iconic journey: a week on horseback through Navajo Nation’s sacred sights.
fields.title: Riding Monument Valley

fields.description: Kayaker Trip Jennings and his crew complete the first source-to-sea descent of the Pandi River.
fields.title: Kayaking Papua New Guinea

fields.description: Writer John Waterman joins biologist George Schaller to explore the nation's most hotly disputed wilderness.
fields.title: ANWR Then & Now

fields.description: Mireya Mayor is not your typical scientist. Both as an anthropologist working in the jungles of Madagascar, and as a wildlife correspondent for National Geographic, this city girl has gone from sleeping in a rain forest to diving with great whites.
fields.title: Mireya Mayor's Wild Life

fields.description: For thousands of years, people have believed that there were once flying monsters. But could they have really existed? In Flying Monsters 3D, Sir David Attenborough, the world’s leading naturalist, sets out to uncover the truth about the enigmatic pterosaurs. Cutting-edge 3-D filming technology and  3-D CGI recreate these spectacular creatures and bring the story of giant flying monsters and their prehistoric world to life. Watch for Flying Monsters 3D, coming to a museum theater near you in October 2011!
fields.title: Flying Monsters 3D

fields.description: Emerging Explorer Kakenya Ntaiya's personal experience inspires her to teach young girls in Kenya.
fields.title: Kakenya Ntaiya, Educator and Activist

fields.description: Join National Geographic on a spectacular journey to witness the most beautiful, powerful, and mysterious weather phenomena in the solar system. From a storm the size of a 100-megaton hydrogen bomb, to a 400-year-old hurricane, to a dust tempest that could engulf entire planets, you'll be glad you live on Earth!  Coming soon to digital fulldome theaters and planetariums worldwide.
fields.title: Wildest Weather in the Solar System

fields.description: When an old villager insists on attending school so he can learn to read, everyone learns that it's never too late to dream.
fields.title: The First Grader

fields.description: Even a baby king cobra has the hunting skills of an adult.
fields.title: King Cobra vs. Olive Water Snake

fields.description: While standing at the U.S.-Mexico border, Emerging Explorer Saleem H. Ali realizes that environmental issues can unite the world.
fields.title: Saleem H. Ali, Environmental Scientist

fields.description: Benda Bilili ("look beyond" in English) tells the powerful story of a remarkable group of disabled street musicians in the African city of Kinshasa where life on the streets can be brutal. Through music and their determination to overcome all obstacles, this downtrodden band helps each other survive the streets and eventually succeeds in bringing their music to the world.
fields.title: Benda Bilili: Combing

fields.description: Follow National Geographic Explorer-in-Residence Bob Ballard and the E/V Nautilus team as they explore ancient history.http://nautiluslive.org/
fields.title: Watch Live: Ballard's Team Searches for Shipwrecks

fields.description: Take a look at Photo Camp New Orleans 2006. The goal of this project  was to document life in New Orleans, seven  months after Hurricane Katrina, as seen through the eyes of fifteen  young people who had returned to their school and homes. Students were  asked to tell their own story, and the story of the city, through  photography and written essays.
fields.title: Photo Camp New Orleans: Seven Months After Hurricane Katrina

fields.description: NG Emerging Explorer Albert Lin describes participating in a Mongolian horse race.
fields.title: Albert Lin, Research Scientist and Engineer

fields.description: Taken from Chilean rapper Ana Tijoux's 2012 sophomore release, <I>La Bala</I>, "Shock" is a political testimony to the massive student protests occurring in Chile and around the world, and a musical snapshot of the current milieu of unrest.
fields.title: Shock

fields.description: Related to the black widow, Australia's redback spider is dangerous like its North American counterpart.
fields.title: Deadly Cousin: The Redback Spider

fields.description: Swim with belugas in this short video.
fields.title: Beluga Whales Swimming

fields.description: Take a behind the scenes look at the Bridger Teton National Forest Avalanche Center. Join as the experts prepare avalanche forecasts for backcountry thrill seekers.
fields.title: Predicting Avalanches

fields.description: Meet Ray Shriver and his avalanche search dog Kita. Learn how dogs can follow their noses to save lives.
fields.title: Avalanche Search Dogs: German Shepherd

fields.description: Richard Leakey proposes a solution to an ancient mystery: how could a  disabled boy have survived in the wild, 1.5 million years ago? Richard,  his wife Meave and daughter Louise Leakey are long-time grantees of  National Geographic.
fields.title: Want to Meet Your Compassionate Ancestors?

fields.description: Elite marathon runner Caitlin Smith shares her passion for long distance running.
fields.title: Running: What's Your Distance?

fields.description: Comb jellies look anything but dangerous. But those pretty, flashing lights can mean death for unwary prey.
fields.title: Neon Killers

fields.description: Wind energy is poised to become a major energy source. Recently, however, people have begun to report problems and complaints with wind turbines built close to houses. There have been some solutions, but the best is to use less energy and conserve, therefore needing less of it. But U.S. government support for renewable energy stills lags. When people begin to see economic and environmental benefits, public attitude won't be far behind.
fields.title: Energy Conservation

fields.description: Sure, love can break your heart. But if you're a male praying mantis, it can literally eat you alive. During mating, the female bites off his head... and then devours his corpse for nourishment.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Deadly Praying Mantis Love

fields.description: Did you know that creating art can be green? Go behind the scenes at a warehouse in Liverpool, England, where old glass bottles and windows become decorative vases and bowls.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Making Art From Recycled Glass

fields.description: They might be the world's smallest monkeys, but these little creatures are ready to rumble when dinner is on the line. A rival group's tree looks inviting; time for a clash of the (tiny) primates.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Smallest Monkey Turf War

fields.description: According to local legends, the aye-aye is a demon that can kill just by pointing a finger. Not quite... but if you're a grub, its bizarre middle digit can be a deadly weapon.
fields.title: The Demon Primate

fields.description: When a freeloader shows up on their turf, a pair of eagles take to the sky for a whirling battle of wills.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Midair Eagle Fight

fields.description: In June 2012, Photo Camp Baltimore brought together young people—refugees from Myanmar (Burma) and Eritrea now living outside the Maryland city—and gave them the tools to tell their stories about what it's like to make a new home. Using photography, writing, and audio recording, the students captured their daily lives and created a portrait. Take a look at their work in this video.
fields.title: Photo Camp Baltimore

fields.description: Don't let a computer failure destroy your precious memories.  Learn how to keep your digital photos safe for years to come.
fields.title: Backup

fields.description: Thanks to super speed and specially-designed feet, the basilisk lizard can run on water... an ability that makes it deadly to insects, and has led people to call it the "Jesus Christ Lizard."
fields.title: Meet the Jesus Christ Lizard

fields.description: Don't call him nosy — a male proboscis monkey needs his big snout to get attention from the ladies. It also amplifies his warning call when he spots a crocodile trying to sneak up on a wading female.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Proboscis Monkeys

fields.description: Follow Klinky and her clan as they take on the challenges of living in the unforgiving Kalahari Desert.  This tale of strength, survival, family and FUN will delight audiences of all ages!
fields.title: Meerkats 3D

fields.description: See the footage Maurizio and his team took with tiny endoscopic cameras carefully placed into the Vasari fresco.
fields.title: Endoscopic View Behind the Vasari

fields.description: With a leg span nearly a foot wide, the goliath bird-eater is the world's biggest spider. And it has a special defense mechanism to keep predators from considering it as a meal.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: World's Biggest Spider

fields.description: De-stress and drift into space with these hypnotic and exotic creatures. Pure escapism for the soul.
fields.title: Dance of the Jellyfish

fields.description: For the burying beetle, life starts out in both the cradle and the grave. These two beetles will bury the body of a shrew underground before laying their eggs inside it.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Raising Kids in a Corpse?

fields.description: Cameras and lenses get dirty. See how to keep them safe while getting them clean.
fields.title: Clean Up Your Act

fields.description: Reflection can be a good thing—in life and photography. But sometimes reflections get in the way.
fields.title: Reflections

fields.description: Avian parents on the Falkland Islands need to stay on high alert. Caracaras are watching... and an unattended nest can easily become a seabird smorgasbord for these vicious predators.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Caracaras Eat Baby Seabirds

fields.description: Once spanning over a million acres of verdant wetlands, the Colorado Delta has been transformed into dry cracked earth and salt flats. Now governments on both sides of the border, as well as Mexican environmental groups and local citizens, work to restore a portion of the delta to its former glory.
fields.title: Locals Help Restore the Colorado Delta

fields.description: Need a little persective? Your photos might too. See how to use perspective to give scale to your photographs of statues, monuments, and landscapes.Like what you see? Get the complete Get Some Perspective photo tip here.
fields.title: Get Some Perspective

fields.description: The "time slice" effect is often used in action movies when actors appear frozen in time as a camera spins around them. Find out how ordinary digital still cameras are used to create this extraordinary special effect.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Camera Special Effects

fields.description: Unsuspecting insects drawn by a light may be in for a surprise—a glowing scorpion waiting to eat them.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: "Glowing" Scorpions Hunt Prey

fields.description: In the quiet Welsh countryside, a rally car is put through a high-octane test before a big rally.
fields.title: I Didn't Know That: Rally Car Testing

fields.description: A snake can track prey using its tongue and nose. But its secret weapon is the Jacobson's organ, a superpowered sensor that helps it detect prey.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Snake's Secret Weapon

fields.description: National Geographic Adventure presents the 2013 Adventurers of the Year, featuring the year's best feats in surfing, climbing, kayaking, snowboarding, skiing, ultrarunning, and more. Vote every day for the 2013 People's Choice Adventurer of the Year, from November 1, 2012, to January 16, 2013, at ngadventure.com.
fields.title: Meet the 2013 Adventurers of the Year

fields.description: For this Australian sea lion, a passing octopus looks like fast food. But the dinner run turns dangerous when the octopus fights back. Ride shotgun with the sea lion in this exclusive footage from National Geographic's Crittercam.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Sea Lion vs. Octopus

fields.description: Follow along as NG Grantee Rhian Waller explores the surprisingly diverse corals that dwell deep in the fjords of the southern tip of South America, and discover what they can tell us about the rest of the ocean as well.
fields.title: Explorer Hits Deep-Sea Coral Jackpot

fields.description: According to CITES, more than 25,000 elephants—an estimated 12 percent of the world's elephant population—were killed in Africa last year alone, and some say the numbers could be much higher. In a new Web series, National Geographic filmmakers share their experiences documenting the illegal ivory trade. Follow journalists Bryan Christy and Aidan Hartley as we go undercover and inside the criminal network behind ivory's supply and demand. Battle for the Elephants airs February 27th at 9PM on PBS. Check local listings.
fields.title: Battle for the Elephants Series Intro: Inside the Ivory Trade

fields.description: When it comes to staying in touch, penguins have the ultimate family plan. Even in a noisy colony of thousands, penguin parents and their chicks can always recognize each other's unique vocalizations.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Penguin Parent Powers

fields.description: In Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, Aidan Hartley attempts to gain access to a maximum-security warehouse that holds perhaps the world's largest cache of raw ivory.Aidan is told the contents of the warehouse have never been filmed, and access to the stockpile is not coming easily. Minister Khamis Kagasheki seeks to give Aidan permission to film, but he meets resistance from his own staff. More about the Massive Ivory Stockpile.
fields.title: Battle for the Elephants Episode 4: Massive Ivory Stockpile

fields.description: Razor-sharp teeth are just the beginning of a shark's arsenal. An array of super-senses helps some sharks detect prey over a mile away.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Shark Superpowers

fields.description: Flying isn't just for the birds. A stretchy membrane and rudder-like tail help this little mammal sail through the treetops, avoiding land-bound predators with ease.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Flying Squirrel

fields.description: This desert showdown pits brains against brawn. Using its wings as a distraction, can a hawk bring down a venomous rattler?
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Rattlesnake vs. Hawk

fields.description: What's a fishing bat's secret weapon? Radar! This skilled predator can catch and consume up to 30 fish every night.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Fishing Bats

fields.description: It's one of nature's weirdest journeys. A newborn kangaroo—barely bigger than a jelly bean—must crawl from one of its mother's two uteri and climb up her body to reach the safety of her pouch!
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Kangaroo Birth

fields.description: Tierney Thys is perhaps best known for her work tracking massive ten-foot-long, 5,000-pound ocean sunfish, or mola, around the globe.  Tierney is not only a champion for the ocean in the scientific world, but also in the world of theater and dance. Tierney conveys an inspiring message of hope, even amidst seemingly constant bad news. "I see incredible hope in the eyes of our children," she says.
fields.title: Reasons for Hope: Tierney Thys on the State of Our Ocean

fields.description: The banded sea snake packs enough poison to kill a human. But to a passing eagle, the snake looks like a tasty—if dangerous—morsel.
fields.title: World's Deadliest: Eagle vs. Toxic Snake

fields.description: When spiny skin isn't enough, the horned lizard repels predators with a truly bizarre tactic: squirting a stream of blood out of its eye.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Blood-Squirting Lizard

fields.description: Most bat species use sonar to locate prey in the dark. But this superpowered bat can hunt using its huge ears alone, flying in "stealth mode" to get the jump on prey.
fields.title: World's Weirdest: Bat Hunts in "Stealth Mode"

fields.description: National Geographic's Emerging Explorer Constanza Ceruti and Explorer-in-Residence Johan Reinhard discover one of the best preserved Incan mummies in the world.
fields.title: Love Your Mummy

fields.description: Digital cameras have lots of image settings to choose from.  Which one is right for you?
fields.title: Shoot JPEG or RAW?

fields.description: When something breaks, what do you do? Repair it or buy a more energy-efficient model?
fields.title: Ailing Appliances

fields.description: How can we protect the Great Lakes? The answer can be found on Lake Michigan.
fields.title: Great Lakes Cleanup

fields.description: Louis Mazzatenta discusses getting in tune with your subject matter.
fields.title: Bullfighter

fields.description: Saving archaeological treasures before looters can do their damage, and investigating past tsunami sites take up most of National Geographic explorers Christina Conlee's and Beverly Goodman's energies.
fields.title: Investigating Cultural Heritage: Secrets of the Past

fields.description: Even the messiest room in the house deserves a cleaner, greener makeover.
fields.title: Personal Care

fields.description: Sometimes the photo you want is just out of reach.  See how a few camera accessories can help you get the shot.
fields.title: Accessories

fields.description: The water-based counterpart to tornadoes, waterspouts have been feared since ancient times.
fields.title: Waterspouts

fields.description: Clean clothes are a must, but so is a clean environment.  Find out how to get both, by following these tips in the laundry room.
fields.title: Laundry Room

fields.description: Greg Anderson, David Harris, Enric Sala, Mike Fay and Jared Diamond discuss the tools and climate that today's explorers operate in.
fields.title: Conservation in the 21st Century

fields.description: Posed group pictures can be nice, but sometimes the really memorable shots are the candid ones. Learn the secrets to capturing impromptu moments.
fields.title: Candid Shots

fields.description: National Geographic explorers Sam Beacham, Malik Marjan, Robert Pitman, and Albert Lin share their stories of unusual places, situations and technology.
fields.title: Frontiers of Exploration - Explorer Symposium

fields.description: Photographer Annie Griffiths Belt shares stories behind the photos in her book A Camera, Two Kids, and a Camel.
fields.title: A Camera, Two Kids, and a Camel

fields.description: Fresh apples and celery root mix with leftover turkey for a delicious and filling salad.
fields.title: Celery Root, Green Apple and Turkey Salad

fields.description: This clip from Pete's Pond, Botswana, captures a family of elephants.  This clan includes a young calf, which was born only a few months ago.  They are regulars at this watering hole and take their time to cool off.
fields.title: The Giants of Pete's Pond

fields.description: Light is changing around you all the time. Learning to see that change is the secret to making outstanding photographs.
fields.title: Using Available Light

fields.description: Immerse yourself in the hypnotic beauty of hundreds of thousands of flamingos that flock to Kenya's famous Lake Bogoria.
fields.title: The Flamingos of Lake Bogoria

fields.description: Private concert in Morocco.
fields.title: Tum Tum Tum — Marrakech

fields.description: Discovering new species, interactive Web tools, animal-borne recorders, and even plagues are daily routines for National Geographic explorers Kris Helgen, Mike Wesch, Katsufumi Sato, and Nathan Wolfe.
fields.title: The Future of Exploration: A Different Lens

fields.description: The music of lamp-making in Morocco.
fields.title: Lamps  — Marrakech

fields.description: What started out as a mission to explore the planets of Jupiter and Saturn has evolved into an adventure to the region beyond our sun's realm. Join a team of interstellar researchers.
fields.title: Voyager Exploring the Solar System

fields.description: Watch as two NASA rovers embark on an incredible journey to uncover the secrets of Mars. Discover how the Martian landscape is similar to Earth's—and how it's very, very different.
fields.title: Mars Rovers

fields.description: In Kenya, a Masaai elder is changing cultural practices that could help HIV infections spread. Learn how education and traditional customs affect the spread of diseases in Africa.
fields.title: Kenya's AIDS Crisis
